}} [[China Guodian Corporation]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|278.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|278|2017}}\n| In August 2017, [[State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission of the State Council|SASAC]] announced that [[China Guodian Corporation]] (one of China's largest coal-fired power generators) and [[Shenhua Group]] (China\u2019s biggest coal miner) would be jointly restructured, with Shenhua Group becoming [[China Energy Investment Corporation]] and absorbing China Guodian Corporation to become the largest power company in the world by installed capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-shenhua-guodian-analysis-idUKKCN1B918C|title=Power of love: China's latest arranged match rattles utilities|first=Meng Meng and Josephine|last=Mason|website=reuters.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907175837/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-shenhua-guodian-analysis-idUKKCN1B918C|archive-date=7 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-shenhua-guodian/china-power-producer-guodian-to-merge-with-shenhua-coal-government-idUSKCN1B80UG|title=China set to create world's top utility with latest government merger|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908113323/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-shenhua-guodian/china-power-producer-guodian-to-merge-with-shenhua-coal-government-idUSKCN1B80UG|archive-date=8 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n| 2015\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China Minmetals]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China Metallurgical Group]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|245.6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|245.6|2015}}\n| In December 2016, China continued its consolidation drive, focussing on their mining sector where China Minmetals Corp took over equipment maker China Metallurgical Group Corp. Minmetals was China\u2019s biggest steel and base metals trader with revenue of more than $50 billion last year, whilst China Metallurgical Group reported revenues of more than $33 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cn-metallurgical-m-a-china-minmetals/minmetals-to-take-over-chinas-mcc-as-part-of-state-reform-government-idUSKBN0TR10M20151208|title=Minmetals takes over MCC as Beijing reforms state-run firms|date=8 December 2015|accessdate=22 November 2017|via=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908154055/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cn-metallurgical-m-a-china-minmetals/minmetals-to-take-over-chinas-mcc-as-part-of-state-reform-government-idUSKBN0TR10M20151208|archive-date=8 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minmetals.com/english/about_666/AboutMinmetals/|title=China Minmetals Corporation|website=www.minmetals.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212045035/http://www.minmetals.com/english/about_666/AboutMinmetals/|archive-date=12 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n| 2017\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sinograin]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China National Cotton Reserves Corp.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|213.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|213|2017}}\n| In January 2017, the Chinese government confirmed the merger of China National Cotton Reserves Corp and Sinograin as part of their drive to reduce the number of State Owned Enterprises to a target of 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-13/china-creates-agriculture-giant-with-grain-cotton-merger|title=China Creates Agriculture Giant With Grain, Cotton Merger|date=13 January 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017|via=www.bloomberg.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901064017/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-13/china-creates-agriculture-giant-with-grain-cotton-merger|archive-date=1 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n| 2018\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[ChemChina]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sinochem]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|120.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|120.0|2018}}\n| Merger of the Chinese state-controlled [[ChemChina]] and [[Sinochem]] in a deal reported to be worth $120 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-chemchina-m-a-sinochem-idUKKBN18J1HR|title=As Syngenta deal closes, ChemChina and Sinochem press $120 billion deal: sources|first=Sumeet Chatterjee and Chen|last=Aizhu|website=reuters.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131421/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-chemchina-m-a-sinochem-idUKKBN18J1HR|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The merger would create the largest entity in the industrial chemicals industry, overtaking [[BASF]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chemanager-online.com/en/news-opinions/headlines/chemchina-and-sinochem-merge-2018|title=ChemChina and SinoChem to Merge in 2018 - chemanager-online.com - Chemistry and Life Science|first=Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co.|last=KGaA|website=www.chemanager-online.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033411/http://www.chemanager-online.com/en/news-opinions/headlines/chemchina-and-sinochem-merge-2018|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/264312/chinese-firms-chemchina-and-sinochem-said-talks-over-mega|title=Chinese firms said to be in mega-merger talks. But do they have chemistry?|first=William|last=Turvill|date=8 May 2017|website=cityam.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042029/http://www.cityam.com/264312/chinese-firms-chemchina-and-sinochem-said-talks-over-mega|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afr.com/business/manufacturing/tieup-between-sinochem-and-chemchina-in-a-class-of-its-own-20170510-gw1gf2#|title=Tie-up between Sinochem and ChemChina in a class of its own|date=10 May 2017|website=afr.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042048/http://www.afr.com/business/manufacturing/tieup-between-sinochem-and-chemchina-in-a-class-of-its-own-20170510-gw1gf2|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/chemchina-sinochem-merger-create-worlds-largest-chem-group/|title=ChemChina-Sinochem merger to create world's largest chem group|website=atimes.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119163742/http://www.atimes.com/article/chemchina-sinochem-merger-create-worlds-largest-chem-group/|archive-date=19 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2020 ChemChina and Sinochem consolidated their agricultural assets into a new holding company, to be called Syngenta Group.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-chemchina-sinochem-syngenta/chemchina-sinochem-merge-agricultural-assets-syngenta-idUKKBN1Z40HB</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\n| 2015\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China Power Investment]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[State Nuclear Power Technology]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|112.6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|112.6|2015}}\n| In June 2015 the Chinese cabinet approved plans to merge state owned China Power Investment (CPIC) with State Nuclear Power Technology increasing the exports of nuclear technology from the country, creating the new entity [[China Power New Energy Development Company Limited]], with assets of more than $112.6 billion) and annual revenues of more than $32.6 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power-technology.com/news/newschina-announces-merger-of-state-nuclear-power-technology-and-the-china-power-investment-4590782|title=China announces merger of State Nuclear Power Technology and the China Power Investment - Power Technology|date=1 June 2015|website=power-technology.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831001232/http://www.power-technology.com/news/newschina-announces-merger-of-state-nuclear-power-technology-and-the-china-power-investment-4590782|archive-date=31 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/C-Chinese-nuclear-giant-officially-launched-1607155.html|title=Chinese nuclear giant officially launched|website=www.world-nuclear-news.org|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701010744/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/C-Chinese-nuclear-giant-officially-launched-1607155.html|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6\n| 2018\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China National Nuclear Corp]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China Nuclear Engineering & Construction ]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|99.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|99|2018}}\n|Merger of China\u2019s second largest nuclear power producer, and their top nuclear power plant builder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-nuclear/china-goes-nuclear-with-latest-state-brokered-power-deal-idUKKBN1FK0S4|title=China goes nuclear with latest state-brokered power deal|first=Josephine|last=Mason|access-date=2018-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131190345/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-nuclear/china-goes-nuclear-with-latest-state-brokered-power-deal-idUKKBN1FK0S4|archive-date=2018-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Largest ever deals which have failed to complete==\nThis lists catalogues M&A (above or equal to $20 billion in transaction value) deals which were confirmed, but for a number of reasons, failed to complete.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>{{nowrap|(in billions USD)}}</small>\n!Inflation adjusted valu