n:center;\"|25.4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|25.4|2004}}\n| Johnson & Johnson announced that it was acquiring Guidant on December 15, 2004, for $76 a share, with the deal being approved on April 27, 2005 by Guidant shareholders. However on May 25 of the same year, Guidant reported 26 cases of implantable defibrillator failure, including a death. Johnson & Johnson announced the possibility of them pulling out from the deal, Guidant then sued Johnson & Johnson in an attempt to enforce the acquisition. However, they later re-negotiated a lower price of $21.5 billion.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/2006/01/25/news/companies/guidant_jnj/index.htm</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 80\n| 2006\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boston Scientific]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Guidant]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|25.0|2006}}\n| A day after [[Johnson & Johnson]] raised their price for Guidant to $23.2 billion, Boston Scientific announced a further increased offer.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/2006/01/25/news/companies/guidant_jnj/index.htm</ref><ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/id/10334047/ns/business-us_business/t/boston-scientific-tops-jj-offer-guidant/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 81\n| 2013\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[The Blackstone Group]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dell]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|25.0|2013}}\n| Blackstone noted in a letter to Dell's special committee that a \"unprecedented 14 percent market decline in PC volume in the first quarter of 2013\" worried the firm and didn't line up with Dell's projections for modest industry growth. In addition, Blackstone's evaluation of Dell showed a \"rapidly eroding financial profile.\" Blackstone subsequently withdrew their bid.<ref>https://www.cnet.com/news/dell-confirms-blackstone-drops-takeover-bid-amid-pc-slump//</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 82\n| 2005\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boston Scientific]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Guidant]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24.6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24.6|2005}}\n| With the re-negotiated lower price of $21.5 billion between Johnson & Johnson and Guidant, Boston Scientific announced an unsolicited offer of $24.6 billion for Guidant (an offer of $72 per share of Guidant, $36 in cash and a fixed number of Boston Scientific shares valued at $36 a share).<ref>https://money.cnn.com/2006/01/25/news/companies/guidant_jnj/index.htm</ref><ref>https://www.vaildaily.com/news/boston-scientific-grants-then-retracts-extension-in-bidding-war-for-guidant/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 83\n| 2006\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Johnson & Johnson]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Guidant]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24.2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24.2|2006}}\n| After [[Boston Scientific]] increased their offer to $25 billion, Johnson & Johnson further increased their offer to $24.2 billion.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/2006/01/25/news/companies/guidant_jnj/index.htm</ref><ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jj-rival-now-leads-guidant-bid-war/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 84\n| 2017\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[PPG Industries]]\n| {{flagicon|NED}} [[Akzo Nobel]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24.1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24.1|2017}}\n| Akzo rejected the unsolicited offer, claiming the revised offer was still too low. <ref>https://fortune.com/2017/03/22/akzo-nobel-ppg-acquisition-rejection/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 85\n| 1998\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Bank of New York]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Mellon Bank Corporation]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24|1998}}\n| Bank of New York called off its takeover proposal after Mellon\u2019s Board declined to meet with Bank of New York officials to discuss the merger. The two would later merge in 2007.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/1998/05/20/deals/mellon//</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 86\n| 2018\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Albertsons]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Rite Aid]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24|2018}}\n| Albertsons and Rite Aid called off the planned merger after several advisory firms recommended voting against the proposal.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/20/albertsons-to-acquire-rite-aid-in-defense-move-against-amazon.html</ref><ref>https://www.supermarketnews.com/retail-financial/albertsons-rite-aid-kill-merger-deal</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 87\n| 2006\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Johnson & Johnson]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Guidant]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23.2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|23.2|2006}}\n| After the re-negotiated lower price of $21.5 billion was trumped by Boston Scientific's offer of $24.6 billion, Johnson & Johnson raised their offer to  $23.2 billion.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/2006/01/25/news/companies/guidant_jnj/index.htm</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/12/business/johnson-raises-bid-for-control-of-guidant.html</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 88\n| 2016\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Mondelez International]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[The Hershey Company]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|23|2016}}\n| Mondelez ceased its pursuit of the Hershey Co acquisition after the chocolate company turned down its $23 billion cash-and-stock offer.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hershey-m-a-mondelez-intl-idUSKCN1142BE</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 89\n| 1995\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tracinda]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Chrysler]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22.8|1995}}\n| Tracinda, led by [[Kirk Kerkorian]], was unable to come up with the financing in order to complete the deal. Chrysler was able to leverage its relationships with investment banks to block Kerkorian from being able to get the money necessary for the takeover.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1995/06/01/kerkorian-withdraws-bid-to-acquire-chrysler-corp/a511c4bd-c437-43a0-a2e8-24a57095f2de/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 90\n| 1996\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[British Telecom]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[MCI Inc.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22|1996}}\n| British Telecom held a partial stake in MCI since 1994 and was looking to acquire the entirety of it. [[Worldcom]] ended up winning the takeover fight with a $37 billion bid..<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/02/business/a-british-company-weighs-buying-mci-in-22-billion-deal.html</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 91\n| 2020\n| {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Seven & i Holdings]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Marathon Petroleum]] <small>([[Speedway LLC]])</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22|2020}}\n| Seven & i walked away from the potential deal, citing concerns over the price.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-speedway-m-a-seven-i-hldgs/japans-seven-i-abandons-22-billion-bid-for-speedway-gas-stations-in-u-s-source-idUKKBN20S11A</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 92\n| 1989\n| {{flagicon|FRA}}{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Sir James Goldsmith]] <br/> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Jacob Rothschild, 4th Baron Rothschild]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Kerry Packer]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[British American Tobacco]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|21|1989}}\n| British American Tobacco rejected the deal as it planned to break up the conglomerate which the company\u2019s chairman [[Patrick Sheehy]] described as \u201cmost disadvantageous to the company, its shareholders, customers, policyholders and employees.\u201d<ref>https://apnews.com/f1f3500b28b47db7883e6adead6633ab</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 93\n| 2014\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Bouygues]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[SFR]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20.6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|20.6|2014}}\n| Bouygues offer was soon trumped by [[Numericable|Numericable's]], who purchased SFR for $23 billion. <ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-04-04/bouygues-sweetens-sfr-bid-again-to-15-billion-euros-in-cash</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 94\n| 2017\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Clariant]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Huntsman Corporation|Huntsman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|20|2017}}\n| After months of pressure from activist investors, the companies announced they would abandon their merger plans, with investors citing a reduction in shareholder value as the cause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-clariant-huntsman-statement/activist-investors-scupper-20-billion-clariant-huntsman-merger-idUKKBN1CW0RI|title=Activist investors scupper $20 billion Clariant-Huntsman merger|first=John Miller and Oliver|last=Hirt|website=reuters.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119012937/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-clariant-huntsman-statement/activist-investors-scupper-20-billion-clariant-huntsman-merger-idUKKBN1CW0RI|archive-date=19 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of largest companies by revenue]]\n* [[List of largest employers]]\n* [[List of companies by profit and loss]]\n* [[List of public corporations by market capitalization]]\n* [[List of largest pharmaceutical mergers and acquisitions]]\n* [[List of largest corporate spin-offs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Corporate finance and investment banking|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of corporate acquisitions|Largest mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Mergers and acquisitions|.]]\n[[Category:Corporation-related lists|Largest mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Economy-related lists of superlatives|Mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Redirect|Megamerger|distributed algorithm in computing|Mega-Merger}}\n\nThe following tables list the largest [[mergers and acquisitions]] in each decade. Transaction values are given in the [[US dollar]] value for the year of the merger, adjusted for inflation. {{As of|2020|3|df=}} the largest ever acquisition was the 1999 takeover of [[Mannesmann]] by [[Vodafone Airtouch PLC]] at $183 billion (${{inflation|US|183|1999}} billion adjusted for inflation). [[AT&T]] appears in these lists the most times with five entries, for a combined transaction value of $311.4 billion. Mergers and acquisitions are notated with the year the transaction was initiated, not necessarily completed. Mergers are shown as the market value of the combined entities.\n\n==Free market enterprises==\n\n===1870s===\nTop M&A deals worldwide by value from 1870 to 1879:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>(in billions USD)</small>\n!<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usinflationcalculator.com/|title=US Inflation Calculator|website=US Inflation Calculator|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028120632/http://www.usinflationcalculator.com/|archive-date=2013-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Inflation adjusted<br/><small>(in billions 2019 USD)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|1879\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pacific Coast Oil Company]]<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=2CHLmPx2PJ0C&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q&f=false</ref>\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Star Oil]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.001\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.024\n|}\n\n===1900s===\nTop M&A deals worldwide by value from 1900 to 1909:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>(in billions USD)</small>\n!<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Inflation adjusted<b