83.aspx The Unexpected Adventure]\", ''[[BuddyTV]]''. Retrieved on March 10, 2008.</ref>\n<ref name=\"FRwRG\">{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|author-link=Michael Ausiello|date=February 7, 2008|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/Big-Problems-Weeks-8078.aspx|title=My Big Problem(s) With This Week's ''Lost''|website=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"gnVTf\">{{cite web|last=Rawson-Jones|first=Ben|date=February 10, 2008|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a89507/s04e02-confirmed-dead-89507/|title-S04E02: 'Confirmed Dead' Review|website=[[Digital Spy]]|access-date=June 21, 2008}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"imdb-entry\">{{IMDb episode|0994359}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Lost (TV series)#Confirmed Dead .5B4.02.5D|\"Confirmed Dead\"}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110318153321/http://abc.go.com/shows/lost/episode-detail/confirmed-dead/80712 \"Confirmed Dead\"] at ABC\n*{{IMDb episode|0994359}}\n*{{tv.com episode|lost/confirmed-dead-1159311}}\n\n{{Lost episodes}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n[[Category:2008 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Lost (season 4) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Drew Goddard]]\n\n[[pt:Lost (temporada 4)#Lista de Epis\u00f3dios]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Arranged references withscript, add archive url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confirmed_Dead"}
{"title_page": "List of zamindari estates in Madras Presidency", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n'''Zamindaris were established in the Madras Presidency''' by the government of the [[British East India Company]] starting from 1799 onwards. These settlements were established in order to delineate authority to landlords and thereby relieve the ryot from the control of middlemen who often exploited them. Often, these [[zamindar]]s were Indian [[Native prince]]s who lost their sovereignty due to British expansion. The zamindari settlement was based on a similar settlement established in Bengal. The Zamindari settlement of Madras was largely unsuccessful and was wrapped up in 1852. However, a few Zamindaris remained till India's independence in 1947.\n\n== Land proprietorship in Madras Presidency ==\nThe colonial [[Madras Presidency]] comprised an area of {{convert|148796|sqmi|km2}}, of which {{convert|141705|sqmi|km2}} were under direct British rule, while the rest was distributed amongst the [[princely state]]s. In the areas administered by the British, three systems of land proprietorship existed: zamindaris, [[inam]]s and [[ryotwari]]s.\n\nIn 1911, zamindari estates covered {{convert|26|e6acre|km2}} and occupied over one-fourth of the total area of the presidency.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Madras (presidency) |volume=17 |page=290}}</ref> In 1945-46, there were {{convert|20945456|acre|km2}} of Zamindari estates which yielded a revenue of 97,83,167 Rupees and {{convert|58904798|acre|km2}} of ''ryotwari'' lands which yielded a revenue of Rs. 7,26,65,330.<ref name=\"statesmanp154\">[[#Statesman|Statesman]], Pg 154</ref>\n\n== Zamindaris from 1799 to 1852 ==\nThe zamindari system was introduced in the Madras Presidency in 1799 in the aftermath of the defeat of the [[Polygars]] in the [[Polygar Wars]].\n\n== Zamindaris in 1877-1920 ==\nIn 1877, C. D.Maclean made a survey of the existing zamindaris under the jurisdiction of Madras Presidency. As per this survey, a few of these zamindaris were larger than some of the smaller princely states in the Presidency. The largest of these were Vizianagaram which is 12,000 sq miles, [[Ramnad estate|Ramnad]], [[Ganapur]] and [[Sivaganga estate|Sivaganga]], Ramnad and Sivaganga being demoted princely states, were larger in size than the princely states of [[Cochin State|Cochin]] or [[Pudukkottai State|Pudukkottai]]. Ramnad, the larger of the two, covered an area of {{convert|2351|sqmi|km2}}, and was second only to [[Travancore State|Travancore]] amongst princely states in Madras Presidency. Karvatinuggur, Kalahasti, Nuzvid, Poonganur, Paralekhemidi and Podile and Darsi divisions of Venkatagiri were larger in size than the princely state of [[Banganapalle]] while Virasanapettah, [[Arni Jagir|Arni estate]] and Kanguni were larger than [[Sandur State|Sandur]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background-color:aqua\" colspan=\"4\"| List of ''zamindari''s in Madras Presidency in the year 1877\n|-\n!  style=\"background-color:aqua\" |Zamindari\n!  style=\"background-color:aqua\" |Area<br /> (in square miles)\n!  style=\"background-color:aqua\" |Population in 1877\n!  style=\"background-color:aqua\" |Revenue paid to the Madras government in 1877<br />(in rupees)\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#99ccff\" colspan=\"4\" align=\"left\"|Chengalpattu district\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Kayapakkam\n| align=\"right\"| 2\n| align=\"right\"|    670\n| align=\"right\"| \n|-\n\n! style=\"background-color:#99ccff\" colspan=\"4\" align=\"left\"|Ganjam district\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Akkayavalasa\n| align=\"right\"| 1\n| align=\"right\"|    788\n| align=\"right\"| 278\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|[[Asika]]\n| align=\"right\"| 3.56\n| align=\"right\"|   7,712\n| align=\"right\"| 4,857\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Athgarh\n| align=\"right\"| 149.37\n| align=\"right\"|    77,228\n| align=\"right\"|  60,000\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Baruva\n| al