ent": "Maddipoti", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_zamindari_estates_in_Madras_Presidency"}
{"title_page": "SM Entertainment", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Sony Music Entertainment}}'''\u03a4\u0395\u0393\u0399\u039f\u039d\u0393\u039a \u0398\u0395\u039f\u03a3, \u03a4\u0395\u0393\u0399\u039f\u039d\u0393\u039a \u0398\u03a1\u0397\u03a3\u039a\u0395\u0399\u0391, \u03a4\u0395\u0393\u0399\u039f\u039d\u0393\u039a \u039f \u039c\u0399\u039a\u03a1\u039f\u03a3 \u0395\u039e\u0395\u03a1\u0395\u03a5\u039d\u0397\u03a4\u0397\u03a3, \u03a4\u0395\u0393\u0399\u039f\u039d\u0393\u039a \u03a0\u03a1\u039f\u0395\u0394\u03a1\u039f\u03a3, \u03a4\u0395\u0393\u0399\u039f\u039d\u039a \u0399\u03a4 \u039c\u03a0\u039f\u03aa, \u03a4\u0395\u0393\u0399\u039f\u039d\u0393\u039a''' \n<br />{{Short description|South Korean entertainment company}}In 2015, SM Entertainment had reported revenues of KR\u20a9325 billion (approximately US$287 million) and a net income of KR\u20a921.7 billion (US$19 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/q/is?s=041510.KQ&annual|title=041510.KQ Income Statement {{!}} S.M. Stock \u2013 Yahoo! UK & Ireland Finance|website=uk.finance.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1989\u20132000: Creation and first generation artists===\nAfter graduating from [[California State University, Northridge]] in the United States, [[Lee Soo-man]] returned to Korea and in 1989 established what was then known as \"SM Studio\" in the [[Apgujeong-dong|Apgujeong]] neighborhood of [[Gangnam District|Gangnam]], [[Seoul]]. In February 1995, the company changed its name to SM Entertainment and set up its capital fund.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Social Media Management: Value Chain and Business Models in Changing Media Markets|last1=Friedrichsen|last2=M\u00fchl-Benninghaus|first1=Mike|first2=Wolfgang|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2013|isbn=978-3-642-28896-8|location=Berlin|page=553}}</ref> SM then developed an in-house production system and created a string of successful artists, including boy band [[H.O.T.]] in 1996, girl group [[S.E.S. (group)|S.E.S.]] in 1997, boy band [[Shinhwa]] in 1998, R&B duo [[Fly to the Sky]] in 1999, and soloist [[BoA]] in 2000.\n\nJung Hae-ik was appointed [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] at the time of SM Entertainment's official reestablishment in 1995,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.daum.net/entertain/newsview?newsid=20130620093605651|title=\uc18c\ub144\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \"\uc774\ub984 \ub54c\ubb38\uc5d0 \ubd81\ud55c \uc544\uc774\ub3cc \uc544\ub2c8\ub0d0\ub354\ub77c\"|website=Daum \uc5f0\uc608|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref>  and was succeeded by Kim Kyung-wook in 1998.\n\n===2000\u20132005: Affiliations and second generation artists===\nThe early 2000s saw the disbandment of both H.O.T (in 2001) and S.E.S (in 2002).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20151111/74708087/1|title=SM Black History|last=|first=|date=2015-11-11|work=news.donga.com|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> Shinhwa departed to a new agency, and new acts like the duo [[Isak N Jiyeon]] and the boy band [[Black Beat]] failed to attain the popularity of previous SM artists.<ref name=\":0\" /> In December 2000, SM established an affiliate company called Fandango Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/157345|title=SM Entertainment merged with Fandango Korea|last=|first=|date=|work=No-Cut News|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko-KR}}</ref> In January 2001, the company founded an overseas division, SM Entertainment Japan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.etoday.co.kr/news/section/newsview.php?idxno=717254|title=Searching for entertainment industry power \u2461. SM entertainment|last=|first=|date=2013-04-12|work=\uc774\ud22c\ub370\uc774|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> Around the same time, the company was approved for listing on [[KOSDAQ]], and SM established an affiliation with the Japanese major label [[Avex Trax]]. SM also formed the subsidiaries BM Entertainment and Cid. K Entertainment (under which the girl groups [[M.I.L.K.]] and [[Shinvi]] were signed, respectively), but they later dissolved when their groups disbanded.\n\nIn late 2002, SM was awarded the Grand Prix of Ministry of Culture and Tourism for the Culture Contents for Export Award in music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://people.incruit.com/column/columnview.asp?bdno=100&colno=386929|title=Lee Soo-man SM Group Leader \u2013 Leader of popular culture industry moving entertainment industry|last=|first=|date=|website=people.incruit.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, SM became affiliated with Starlight Corporation Ltd. and C-Cube Entertainment Corporation. That same year, the company debuted five-member boy group [[TVXQ]]. The following years saw the debuts of artists such as [[TRAX (band)|TRAX]] (2004), [[The Grace (band)|The Grace]] (2005), and [[Super Junior]] (2005).\n\n===2005\u20132010: Expansion and international artists===\nIn 2005, Kim Young-min became the company's third CEO,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2016/03/386_192565.html|title=After 20 years, SM Entertainment to expand overseas base|date=2015-12-07|website=koreatimes|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> under whom several artists debuted with a view to promoting outside of South Korea. Artists produced by SM during this period included Chinese-born soloist [[Zhang Liyin]] (2006), Japanese-language soloist [[J-Min]] (2007), [[Girls' Generation]] (2007), [[Shinee]] (2008), and [[F(x) (band)|f(x)]] (2009). In April 2008, SM debuted a Mandarin-language sub-unit of Super Junior, named [[Super Junior-M]]. In October 2008, SM announced plans for BoA's debut in the American market, under a newly formed subsidiary label named SM Entertainment USA.\n\nIn May 2008, the SM Art Company opened under co-CEO Pyo In-bong, with a focus on producing theatrical works. The company's first venture was a production of the American musical comedy [[Xanadu (musical)|''Xanadu'']], starring Super Junior members [[Heechul]] and [[Kangin]].<ref>Koh Young-aah [http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20080530000048 \"Super Junior members set to make move into musicals\"] ''Korea Herald''. 30 May 2008. Retrieved 3 April 2012.</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132012: Joint and further ventures===\n{{see also|SM Culture & Contents}}\nIn February 2010, after two decades on SM Entertainment's board of directors, founder Lee Soo-man resigned from his position in order to \"focus more energy on SM's overseas business, new business management, and artist development.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010022514424957673|title=Lee Soo-man steps down from SM board of directors|last=Kun-ouc|first=Park|date=25 February 2010|newspaper=10 Asia|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> In March of the same year, [[KMP Holdings]] was established as a joint venture between SM Entertainment, [[YG Entertainment]], [[JYP Entertainment]], [[Star Empire Entertainment|Star Empire]], Medialine, CAN Entertainment, and Music Factory.<ref>[http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?sc=30000019&cm=%EC%A6%9D%EA%B6%8C%20%EC%A3%BC%EC%9A%94%EA%B8%B0%EC%82%AC&year=2010&no=138710&selFlag=&relatedcode=&wonNo=&sID=502 \"Korean Music Power: KMP Holdings Co. Ltd. Launched!\"] ''[[Maeil Kyungje]]''. 18 March 2010. Retrieved 2012-10-06 {{in lang|ko}}</ref> The firm's first release from SM was Super Junior's fifth studio album, ''[[Mr. Simple]]'', which marked the end of SM's self-distribution. In May, SM announced its highest ever first quarter operating profits, at KR{{SK won|10.4&nbsp;billion}}, up 471% from the same period the previous year. Gross revenue was reported at KR{{SK won|22.7&nbsp;billion}}, a 58% increase on the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010051314034381443|title=SM Entertainment records biggest Q1 profit|last=Kim|first=Lynn|date=13 May 2010|newspaper=10 Asia|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, SM Entertainment, YG Entertainment, JYP Entertainment, KeyEast, AMENT, and Star J Entertainment came together to form United Asia Management, a joint investment agency geared towards advancing Asian music worldwide. That August, SM joined with Thai media company [[TrueVisions]] to create an international joint venture, SM True.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=109&aid=0002241539|title=SM \uc5d4\ud130, \ud0dc\uad6d\uc11c \uccab \ud574\uc678 \ud569\uc791\ubc95\uc778 'SM True' \uc124\ub9bd|date=17 August 2011|newspaper=Naver News|language=Korean|trans-title=SM Entertainment establishes joint venture company with Thailand\u2019s True Visions Group, \u2018SM True\u2019|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Super_Junior_performs_at_the_MTV_EXIT_Hanoi_Concert_2010.jpg|thumb|[[Super Junior]] at the MTV Exit Hanoi Concert in 2010.]]\nIn 2012, SM debuted the large-scale boy group [[Exo (band)|EXO]], split into two units in order to promote in Korea and China simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20120127n03950?mid=e0101|title=SM \uc0c8 \uadf8\ub8f9 EXO, 30\uc77c \ud504\ub864\ub85c\uadf8 \uc2f1\uae00 \uacf5\uac1c|website=\ub124\uc774\ud2b8\ub274\uc2a4|language=ko-KR|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref> In February, SM acquired Hawaiian travel firm Happy Hawaii and launched SMTown Travel, a new business initiative specializing in travel and tourism under Kang Jung-hyun.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stviewEng.php?type=3&no=2012022714534028406|title=SM Entertainment takes over travel agency|last=Mun|first=Wan-Sik|date=27 February 2012|newspaper=Star News|access-date=1 May 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824075531/http://star.mt.co.kr/stviewEng.php?type=3&no=2012022714534028406|archive-date=24 August 2012|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smtowntravel.com/|title=SM Global Package On Sale!|website=www.smtowntravel.com|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref> Later that year, SMTown Travel offered package deals for overseas fans attending Super Junior's ''[[Super Show 4 Tour]]'' encore concerts in Seoul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=5801|title=Super Junior to Hold Encore Concert in Seoul in May|last=Ho|first=Stewart|date=23 April 2012|publisher=CJ E&M|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref> In March, 47 of SM Entertainment's recording artists became stockholders of the company. Kangta, BoA, and most members of Super Junior and Girls\u2019 Generation received 680 shares each (with a value of approximately US$27,200 per person), while members of more recent groups like Shinee and f(x) received 340 shares each (with a value of around US$13,600 per person).<ref>Kim, JiYeon [http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201203271706_4801&nowPage=4 \"SM Artists Take on SM Stock\"] ''Mnet News''. 27 March 2012. Retrieved 30 March 2012.</ref> In August, SM held an art exhibition at the [[COEX Convention & Exhibition Center]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2957706|title=Fantasies come true at the high-tech SM ART exhibit|last=Kim|first=Hyung-eun|date=10 August 2012|newspaper=Joongang Daily|access-date=6 October 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126203405/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2957706|archive-date=26 January 2013|df=}}</ref> and collaborated with Visa and KB Kookmin Card to begin printing SM artist cards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://media.daum.net/culture/others/newsview?newsid=20120726091412600|title=SM \uccb4\ud06c\uce74\ub4dc \ub098\uc628\ub2e4, VISA-KB\uad6d\ubbfc\uce74\ub4dc\uc640 MOU\uccb4\uacb0|date=26 July 2012|newspaper=Daum|language=Korean|trans-title=SM Entertainment to make MOU contract with VISA and KB Card|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> That same month, Korean TV personalities [[Kang Ho-dong]] and [[Shin Dong-yup (entertainer)|Shin Dong-yup]] announced that they had signed exclusive contracts with SM's new broadcasting subsidiary, [[S.M. Culture & Contents|SM Culture & Contents]] (SM C&C), marking SM's expansion into television.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=12644|title=Kang Ho Dong Announces Return by Signing with SM C&C|last=Lee|first=JinHo|date=17 August 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=12700|title=Three Reasons Why Kang Ho Dong Signed with SM|last=Choi|first=Eunhwa|date=18 August 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> The next month, in September, SM C&C merged with AM Entertainment (which then represented top actors such as [[Jang Dong-gun]], [[Kim Ha-neul]], and [[Han Ji-min]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=15384|title=SM C&C Takes Over AM Entertainment \u2013 Home to Jang Dong Gun, Kim Ha Neul and Others|last=Ho|first=Stewart|date=19 September 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> and two other TV personalities, [[Lee Su-geun]] and [[Kim Byung-man]], announced that they had also signed with SM.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=15399|title=Lee Su Geun, Kim Byung Man Join Kang Ho Dong at SM C&C?|last=Ho|first=Stewart|date=19 September 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> In November, KMP Holdings was acquired by [[KT Corporation|KT Music]], and in June 2013, KT Music absorbed KMP's distribution network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kt.com/eng/pr/news_01_view.jsp|title=(kt PR room) KT to acquire KMP Holdings to strengthen its music businesses|date=November 23, 2012|publisher=[[KT Corporation]]|accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u2013present: Third generation artists and ScreaM Records===\n{{see also|SM Rookies|Label SJ|SM Station}}\n[[File:Smentertainment_logo.jpg|thumb|Company logo until October 2017]]\nIn 2013, SM C&C acquired Hoon Media (a production company led by Lee Hoon-hee, responsible for KBS serials ''[[1 vs. 100#International variants|1 vs 100]]'', ''[[Heroine 6|Heroines 6]]'', ''[[Qualifications of Men]]'', and ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'') and [[Woollim Entertainment]], a record label responsible for artists such as [[Infinite (band)|Infinite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpopasia.com/news/sm-entertainment-acquires-woollim-entertainment-creates-new-sublabel::14629.html|title=SM Entertainment Acquires Woollim Entertainment, Creates New Sublabel|last=Aysohmay|first=|date=9 August 2013|website=Jpopasia|publisher=Jpopasia|access-date=20 April 2016}}</ref> In January 2014, SM and the other six talent agencies behind [[KMP Holdings]] formed a collective bond partnership and bought 13.48% of [[KT Music]]'s stocks, leaving parent [[KT Corporation]] with 49.99%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/news/news_view.php?f_seq=103&sgenre=issue |title=SM, YG, JYP lead 7 companies as KT Music's new stakeholders |author=Cho Seung-hoon |date=January 24, 2014 |work=[[Gaon Music Chart]] |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association. |access-date=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006080320/http://gaonchart.co.kr/news/news_view.php?f_seq=103&sgenre=issue |archive-date= 6 October 2014 |df= }}</ref> In February, SM acquired a share in [[Baljunso]], an indie record label founded in 1991 by Kang Byung-yong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/59613/sm-invests-in-indie-label|title=KPOP NEWS \u2013 SM Entertainment Invests in Indie Label Baljunso to Spotlight Nonmainstream Music {{!}} Mwave|website=mwave.interest.me|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> On August 1, SM debuted [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]], its first girl group since f(x) five years prior.\n\nIn August 2015, SM partnered with sports marketing company IB Worldwide to create Galaxia SM, responsible for golfer [[Inbee Park|Park In-bee]], gymnast [[Son Yeon-jae]], and [[Shin-Soo Choo|Choo Shin-soo]], right fielder for the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].<ref>''[[Korea Times]]'': [http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/08/201_185635.html SM, IB Worldwide ink deal to create 'sportainment']</ref> On November 6, the 10th anniversary of [[Super Junior]]'s debut, SM announced the creation of the group's own sub-label, [[Label SJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/99582/exclusive-super-junior-label-lable-sj-established-for-10-year-anniversary|title=KPOP NEWS \u2013 Exclusive Super Junior Label \u2032Lable SJ\u2032 &#91;sic&#93; Established for 10th Anniversary|website=Mwave|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> In late 2015, SM partnered with modeling company ESteem to promote self-owned content and network.[[SM Entertainment#cite note-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]] The venture later expanded its acting division through the acting debuts of models Ki Do-hoon and Lee Cheol-woo.oo.\n\nIn January 2016, founder Lee Soo-man held a conference at the SM Coex Artium, announcing plans for a new boy group, [[NCT (band)|NCT]] (Neo Culture Technology), with \"unlimited members\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201601271758282555044_2|title=SM Entertainment\u2019s next boy band to have 'unlimited' members|website=kpopherald.koreaherald.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/korea-firm-unveils-k-pop-band-limitless-members-104640224--finance.html?ref=gs|title=S. Korea firm unveils K-pop band with limitless members|website=www.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> The first unit of this group, NCT U, released its first two singles in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2016/04/386_201890.html|title=SM's new K-pop band NCT U to debut this week|date=2016-04-04|website=koreatimes|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> NCT has since expanded to three more units - the South Korea-based fixed unit [[NCT 127]] in July 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hype.my/2016/113666/nct127-sm-entertainment-unveils-members-of-new-nct-sub-unit/|title=(UPDATE) #NCT127: SM Entertainment Unveils Members Of New NCT Sub-Unit|website=Hype|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> the youth/teen-aged unit [[NCT Dream]] in August 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/music/now/read?oid=108&aid=0002548916|title=NCT DREAM, \ub370\ubdd4\uace1 '\uce04\uc789\uac80' 25\uc77c '\uc5e0\uce74'\uc11c \uccab\uc120|date=August 19, 2016|website=Naver|publisher=Star Money|language=ko}}</ref> and the China-based [[WayV]] in January 2019.<ref name=\"WayV\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2019/01/16/wayv-represents-sm-entertainments-goals-for-global-dominance-through-cultural-technology/|title=WayV Represents SM Entertainment's Goals For Global Dominance Through Cultural Technology|last=Herman|first=Tamar|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> WayV is being managed by their own sub-label, Label V.<ref name=\"WayV\" />\n\nAt the beginning of the year, the company opened a restaurant, SMT Seoul,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pulsenews.co.kr/view.php?sc=30800022&year=2016&no=59733|title=SM Entertainment opens up-scale restaurant SMT Seoul \u2013 Pulse by Maeil Business News Korea|website=pulsenews.co.kr|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> and also established a series of stores selling branded foods under the name SUM Market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.joins.com/article/19582509|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] SM\uc5d4\ud130, \ubcf8\uc0ac\uc5d0 \u2018\uc5d1\uc18c \ud3b8\uc758\uc810\u2019 \uc5f0\ub2e4\u2026\uc9c0\ub09c\ud574 \ub9d0 \uc774\uc218\ub9cc-\uc815\uc6a9\uc9c4 \ub9cc\ub098 \ubc11\uadf8\ub9bc|date=2016-02-17|website=news.joins.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> On February 11, 2016, the Chinese e-commerce giant [[Alibaba Group]] acquired a 4 percent minority stake in SM Entertainment for US$30 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kang|first1=John|title=Why Alibaba Bought $30M Stake In K-Pop Giant SM Entertainment, Home To EXO And Girls' Generation|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johnkang/2016/02/11/why-alibaba-bought-30m-stake-in-k-pop-giant-sm-entertainment-home-to-exo-and-girls-generation/#7e130efda556|work=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, SM released the first single under its newly established [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] label ScreaM Records, \"Wave\", featuring [[F(x) (band)|f(x)]] members Amber and Luna and produced by Xavi & Gi and E-mart's Electro Mart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160426000798|title=SM\u2019s EDM label to drop first track|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=109&aid=0003305800|title=SM, EDM\ub808\uc774\ube14 'ScreaM Records' \uc124\ub9bd..5\uc6d46\uc77c \uccab\uace1 \ubc1c\ud45c|website=Naver|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> ScreaM Records opened as part of SM's New Culture Technology 2016 project, under which SM also initiated the digital music channel [[SM Station]] and a number of mobile apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreadailyus.com/introducing-nct-how-sm-entertainment-is-taking-advantage-of-digital-platforms-to-take-over-the-global-entertainment-market/|title=Introducing NCT: How SM Entertainment is taking advantage of digital platforms to take over the global entertainment market|last=Yi|first=Lily|website=www.koreadailyus.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> In late 2016, SM began organizing a ''[[League of Legends]]'' tournament called  SM Super Celeb League, in which SM artists [[Heechul]] and [[Byun Baek-hyun|Baekhyun]] played against both professional gamers and fans from South Korea and China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.inven.co.kr/webzine/news/?news=166742&iskin=esports|title='\uae40\ud76c\ucca0-\ubc31\ud604' \ucc38\uc5ec! \ud32c\uacfc \ud568\uaed8 \ud558\ub294 \uc911\uad6d LoL \uc774\ubca4\ud2b8\uc804|website=inven.co.kr|date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2017, a source from the task force in charge of the ''international K-pop academy'' has plans to open this upcoming September. The Gangnam-based academy is a collaborative venture with the private Jongro Sky Academy. Plans for the school to be certified as an alternative program for domestic Korean middle and high school education, as well as US secondary school education, are also underway.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insight.co.kr/newsRead.php?ArtNo=94073|title=SM, \uc62c\ud574 9\uc6d4 \uac15\ub0a8 \ud55c\ubcf5\ud310\uc5d0 'K\ud31d \uad6d\uc81c\ud559\uad50' \uac1c\uad50\ud55c\ub2e4|website=insight.co.kr|date=February 16, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, SM acquired the independent record label [[Mystic Entertainment]], becoming the label's largest shareholder.<ref>[http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002602163] star.mt 2017/03</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, SM opened its Indonesian office in Jakarta.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.viva.co.id/showbiz/gosip/1118974-5-spot-foto-lucu-di-kantor-sm-entertainment-jakarta|title=5 Spot Foto Lucu di Kantor SM Entertainment Jakarta|date=2019-02-08|website=VIVA.co.id|access-date=2019-09-08|language=Indonesian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jawapos.com/entertainment/music-movie/08/02/2019/ada-kantor-cabang-sm-entertainment-di-indonesia-bakal-gelar-audisi/|title=Ada Kantor Cabang, SM Entertainment di Indonesia Bakal Gelar Audisi|date=2019-02-08|website=[[Jawa Pos|JawaPos.com]]|access-date=2019-09-08|language=Indonesian|editor1-last=Purnamasari|editor1-first=Deti Mega}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2019, SM and [[Capitol Music Group]] \u2013 which earlier signed NCT 127 in April 2019<ref name=\"Capitol\">{{cite web|last1=Cirisano|first1=Tatiana|title=Capitol Music Group & Caroline Sign K-Pop Stars NCT 127 to Distribution Deal|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8505641/nct-127-capitol-music-group-caroline-distribution-deal|website=[[billboard]]|accessdate=April 5, 2019|date=April 4, 2019}}</ref> \u2013 announced [[SuperM]], a [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] consisting of [[Lee Tae-min|Taemin]] from Shinee, [[Byun Baek-hyun|Baekhyun]] and [[Kai (entertainer, born 1994)|Kai]] from Exo, and [[Lee Tae-yong|Taeyong]], [[Ten (singer)|Ten]], [[Lucas Wong|Lucas]] and [[Mark Lee (singer)|Mark]] from NCT units NCT 127, NCT Dream and WayV, in the 2019 Capitol Congress event in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"SuperM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/08/07/super-m-the-avengers-of-k-pop-unveiled-by-sm-entertainment-and-capitol-music-group/ |title=Super M, 'The Avengers Of K-Pop,' Unveiled By SM Entertainment And Capitol Music Group |last=Benjamin |first=Jeff |date=August 7, 2019 |website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |publisher= |access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref> The group debuted in October 2019.<ref name=\"SuperM\" />\n\nIn November 2019, SM Entertainment signed with [[Creative Artists Agency]] for representation in all areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/k-pop-powerhouse-sm-entertainment-home-to-nct-127-superm-and-exo-inks-with-caa-1203392415/ |title=K-Pop Powerhouse SM Entertainment, Home to NCT 127, SuperM and EXO, Inks With CAA |last=Kim |first=Jae-Ha |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher= |access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries==\nSource:<ref name=\"GROUP COMPANIES\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smentertainment.com/Overview/Affiliate|title=SM Entertainment GROUP COMPANIES |publisher=SM Entertainment|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[SM Culture & Contents|SM C&C]] (2012)\n* Dream Maker Entertainment\n* SM Life Design Group Co., Ltd (2018)\n* SM True (2011)\n* SM Brand Marketing (2008)\n* Everysing (2017)\n* Galaxia SM (2004)\n* [[Million Market]] (2018)\n* SM Japan (2001)\n* [[KeyEast]] (2018)\n* SM USA (2008)\n* SM F&B Development (2008)\n* SM TOWN Planner (2017)\n* [[ESteem Entertainment|ESteem]] (2015)\n* [[Mystic Story]] (2017)\n\n==Artists==\n{{main|SM Town|SM Entertainment artists}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|SM Entertainment discography}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|SM Culture & Contents#Filmography}}\n\n==Controversies==\n===Contractual disputes===\n====JYJ (TVXQ)====\nIn late July 2009, three of the five original members of SM Entertainment boy group [[TVXQ]] \u2013 [[Kim Jaejoong]], [[Park Yoochun]], and [[Kim Junsu]] \u2013 applied to the Seoul Central District Court to investigate the validity of their contract with SM,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/08/178_49459.html|title=TVXQ Feuds With SM Entertainment|date=2009-08-02|work=The Korea Times|accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10167 |title=Is TVXQ Headed for Breakup? |date=2009-08-03 |work=KBS World |access-date=3 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105210213/http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10167 |archive-date=5 January 2010 |df= }}</ref> as they felt the thirteen-year contract was excessively long and that earnings were not fairly distributed to the members,<ref name=\"lawsuit2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/08/178_49540.html|title=TVXQ to Stick Together Despite Legal Dispute|date=2009-08-03|work=The Korea Times|accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref> but contract destruction, they shall be compensated to the Employer by three times the total investment amount and two times the ordinary profit during the remaining contract period.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/08/04/2009080401107.html|title=TVXQ is a 'slave contract' ... SM, 'quasi-fraud'|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> The news of this dispute caused SM Entertainment's [[KOSPI]] stock price to drop by 10.06%.<ref>Thomson Reuters. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090806092540/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2009/08/03/afx6730465.html Korea Hot Stocks \u2013 Hankook Tire, SM Ent, Ssangyong Motor]. ''[[Forbes.com]]''. August 3, 2009. Retrieved 3 August 2009.</ref> In addition, 120,000 fans of TVXQ filed a petition against SM's long-term contracts to the Seoul Central District Court, and also filed for compensation for an SMTown Live Concert that was canceled a week before its scheduled date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10351 |title=TVXQ Fan Club Files for Compensation for Cancelled Concert |date=2009-09-03 |work=KBS World |access-date=3 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030203834/http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10351 |archive-date=30 October 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\nTheir statement read, \"(They) have had health problems and finally reached their physical limits, but SM Entertainment continued to send them abroad and plan excessive activities. Thus, the three members have started to hope they will be able to continue their careers as they wish, instead of being used as tools for the agency's profits.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sang-hee|first1=Han|title=TVXQ to Stick Together Despite Legal Dispute|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/08/178_49540.html|website=The Korea Times|publisher=The Korea Times Co.|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe court ruled in the favour of the three ex-members. In response, SM held a press conference claiming that the lawsuit was fraudulent, and filed an injunction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10760|title=SM Entertainment Calls the TVXQ Suit a Big Fraud|date=2009-11-02|work=KBS World|accessdate=2 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/02/18/2011021801086.html|title=JYJ Win Legal Battle with Former Management|date=18 February 2011|work=Chosun Ilbo|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref> In early May 2010, it was announced that Jaejoong, Yoochun, and Junsu would return to the stage as [[JYJ]] under a new management agency, [[C-JeS Entertainment]].<ref>[http://kr.news.yahoo.com/service/news/shellview.htm?articleid=2010052010224117308&linkid=4&newssetid=1352 \"\uc2dc\uc544\uc900\uc218 \ub4f1 \ub3d9\ubc29\uc2e0\uae30 3\uc778, \uc0c8 \uadf8\ub8f9 \uc774\ub984\uc740 J.Y.J?\"] ''Yahoo News''. 20 May 2010. Retrieved 2012-10-06 {{in lang|ko}}</ref> The injunction was dismissed by the Seoul Central District Court on February 17, 2011, and the final decision on the case was postponed indefinitely for mediation under the justice department.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/02/18/2011021801086.html|title=JYJ Win Legal Battle with Former Management|work=Chosun Ilbo|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=15363|title=Decision on JYJ vs. SM Entertainment Case Postponed Indefinitely for Mediation|last=Park|first=HyunMin|date=19 September 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 2012, during a voluntary arbitration at the Seoul Central District Court, SM Entertainment and JYJ reached a mutual agreement to terminate all contracts between the two parties and not to interfere with each other's activities in the future, concluding the lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2963083|title=JYJ and SM finally reach agreement|last=Sunwoo|first=Carla|date=29 November 2012|newspaper=Joongang Daily|access-date=5 December 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130111053417/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2963083|archive-date=11 January 2013|df=}}</ref> SM reportedly stated that they had decided to end the litigation \"to avoid bringing additional harm to U-Know Yunho and Max Changmin, who are active as TVXQ, and to avoid making any more unneeded issues.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=22343|title=SM and JYJ Put an End to Their Long, Winding Legal Suit|date=28 November 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=5 December 2012|author=Park, HyunMin|author2=Erika Kim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2012112813495846832|title=JYJ, SM Come to Agreement Regarding Exclusive Contract Issue|last=Lee|first=Tae Ho|date=28 November 2012|newspaper=10 Asia|accessdate=5 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Han Geng====\nOn December 21, 2009, five months after the three former TVXQ members filed their lawsuit and while the dispute was still active, [[Han Geng]], the only Chinese member of [[Super Junior]], also filed a lawsuit against SM. Han Geng filed for similar reasons: unfair profit distribution, and an unfair thirteen-year contract that contained provisions in SM's favor that he was not allowed to revise or end.<ref>[http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2009122215270135930&type=1&outlink=1 \"\ud55c\uacbd \"SM, \u975e\uc815\uc0c1\uc801 \ud65c\ub3d9\uac15\uc694\"] ''Star News''. 22 December 2009. Retrieved 2012-05-01 {{in lang|ko}}</ref> The artist's friend and later manager Sun Le also submitted a statement to the Korean courts citing SM Entertainment's violation of Han Geng's rights, which was later leaked via the internet.<ref>[http://community.livejournal.com/geng_bao/76937.html#cutid1 \"Exclusive Interview with Han Geng's Team\"] (In Chinese with English Translation) ''Beijing Youth Weekly Magazine'' 25 August 2010. Retrieved 1 May 2012.</ref> The statement argued that SM had discriminated against Han Geng financially as well as in terms of management.\n\nOn September 27, 2011, Han Geng's departure from Super Junior was made official when legal representatives of both Han Geng and SM released a joint statement saying that \"Han Geng and SM Entertainment have amicably settled on a mutual agreement, and the lawsuit was able to come to a close after Han Geng submitted his 'Notice of Withdrawal of Appeal.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=382&aid=0000011661|title=SM Entertainment's official position: Han Geng has \"come to a mutual agreement, and will terminate proceedings\"|date=September 2011|publisher=news.naver.com|accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?a_id=2011092711070333667 |title=Han Geng's official position: \"SM Entertainment has amicably agreed\" |date=September 2011 |publisher=10asia.co.kr |access-date=10 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017220337/http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?a_id=2011092711070333667 |archive-date=17 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n====Kris Wu====\nOn May 15, 2014, [[Kris Wu]], a Chinese-Canadian member of [[Exo (band)|EXO]], filed a lawsuit to terminate his contract with SM, as first reported by Chinese news portal Sina.<ref name=\"ent.sina.com.cn2\">{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/y/k/2014-05-15/09314141917.shtml|title=EXO-M\u961f\u957f\u5434\u4ea6\u51e1\u63d0\u51fa\u89e3\u7ea6 SM\u518d\u9677\u89e3\u7ea6\u95e8|work=sina.com.cn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140515000936|title=EXO-M\u2019s Kris sues SM to end exclusive contract|author=The Korea Herald|work=koreaherald.com}}</ref> He was represented by Cho Bum-suk, the same lawyer that handled [[Han Geng]]'s case. Kris, whose real name is Wu Yifan, was quoted as saying, \"The company has treated me like a machine part or as an object of control rather than presenting a vision as an entertainer.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Phillip |title=SM Entertainment\u2019s lawsuit history over \u2018unfair contracts\u2019 |url=http://www.hellokpop.com/news/sm-entertainments-lawsuit-history-over-unfair-contracts/ |website=HelloKpop |publisher=hellokpop.com |accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> He left the group in the same month that the lawsuit was made public, while the rest of the group continued to promote their single \"Overdose.\" On July 21, 2016, Kris officially parted ways with EXO, although his contract with SM remains valid until 2022.<ref name=\"LuKrisConclu\">{{cite web|last1=Alexander|first1=Kevin|title=Kris And Luhan's Contract Lawsuit Against SM Entertainment Ends|url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/273224/20160722/sm-entertainment-lawsuit-kris-luhan-sue-end-conclusion-negotiation-contract.htm|website=KPOPStarz|accessdate=23 July 2016|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Jessica Jung====\nOn September 29, 2014, [[Girls' Generation]] member [[Jessica Jung]] claimed in a [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]] post that she had been forced out of the group, writing:<blockquote>''I was excited about our upcoming fan events only to shockingly be informed by my company and 8 others that as of today, I'm no longer a member. I'm devastated \u2013 my priority and love is to serve as a member of GG, but for no justifiable reason, I am being forced out''.<ref>[http://www.weibo.com/3547642417/Bpknsn8y8 Jung's Weibo update on September 30, 2014] weibo.com (September 30, 2014). Retrieved 30 September 2014.</ref></blockquote>The following day, Jung released a statement claiming that in August 2014 her fellow group members and SM had been positive about the launch of her fashion business, Blanc and Eclare. As of early September, she claimed, they had all changed their stance, and she was directed to either close the business or cease promotions as a member of Girls' Generation. She claimed to have received the day before a \"one-sided notice\" asking her to leave the group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/v/1e23e60b787c4ff4b3f63162baa02eff|title=Jessica's exits Girl's Generation|last=|first=|date=2014-09-30|work=\ud55c\uad6d\uc77c\ubcf4|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nHowever, according to SM, Jung had unilaterally informed them in early spring that she would leave the group after one more album. But before agreements could be made, she had set up her independent business, which caused problems for the group's professional schedules. This prompted management to begin promoting Girls' Generation as eight members rather than nine, with the intention of announcing the news; however, Jung had already \"posted her own perspective\u201d. The company then stated that the group would henceforth continue as eight, while they would still manage Jung's individual schedule.<ref>[http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/77155/sm-makes-official-statement-on-jessica SM States that SNSD will Promote as Eight Without Jessica] CJ E&M enewsWorld (September 30, 2014). Retrieved 23 February 2016.</ref> In the days immediately after this news came to light, company stocks dropped by KR\u20a93,350 per share, from KR\u20a940,750 to KR\u20a937,400, losing SM a total of KR\u20a969 billion (approximately US$65&nbsp;million).{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nOn August 6, 2015, Jung and SM Entertainment reached an agreement to terminate her contract, with Jung stating, \"This release is to confirm that SM Entertainment ('SM') and I have officially parted ways. I will cherish the many years we spent and I wish SM the best of luck in all of its endeavors.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=kiddy_days|title=Former Girls\u2019 Generation Member Jessica Officially Leaves SM Entertainment|url=https://www.soompi.com/2015/08/05/former-girls-generation-member-jessica-officially-leaves-sm-entertainment/|website=Soompi|publisher=Viki Inc.|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Lu Han====\nOn October 10, 2014, [[Luhan (singer)|Lu Han]] became the second Chinese member of [[Exo (band)|EXO]] to file to nullify his contract with SM Entertainment and leave the group, just over four months after Kris had done the same.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=581895|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \ub8e8\ud55c, SM\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\uc5d0 \uc18c\uc1a1\u2026\ud06c\ub9ac\uc2a4 \ub4a4 \uc787\ub098|website=TV\ub9ac\ud3ec\ud2b8|language=ko-KR|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201410101029561131&ext=na|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \ub8e8\ud55c, SM\uc5d0 \uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d \ud574\uc9c0\uc18c\uc1a1\u2026\ud06c\ub9ac\uc2a4\uc640 \uac19\uc740 \ud589\ubcf4|website=www.mydaily.co.kr|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201410101325541210|title=SM \"\ub8e8\ud55c \uac11\uc791\uc2a4\ub7f0 \uc18c\uc1a1 \ub2f9\ud639, \ubc30\ud6c4\uc138\ub825 \uc758\uc2ec\ub41c\ub2e4\" \uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5|website=www.newsen.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> His lawsuit included the claim that SM had favored the Korean sub-unit EXO-K over the Chinese sub-unit EXO-M. Within 15 minutes of the announcement, company stocks had dropped by 9.41%, from KR\u20a937,000 to KR\u20a933,250 per share.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} The stock's worth contracted by 15%, hitting the maximum decrease in price KOSDAQ allows for a day, and falling to a more-than-one-year low.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2014/10/10/exo-member-luhan-files-lawsuit-to-leave-k-pop-group/|title=EXO Member Luhan Files Lawsuit To Leave K-Pop Group|last=Lee|first=Min-Jeong|date=10 October 2014|website=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> On July 21, 2016, Lu Han officially parted ways with EXO, although his contract with SM remains valid until 2022.<ref name=\"LuKrisConclu\" />\n\n====No Min-woo====\nIn April 2015, [[No Min-woo]], a former member of [[TraxX|TRAX]], filed a lawsuit against SM for subjecting him to an unlawful seventeen-year contract.<ref name=\"culture line\">{{cite web | title = No Min-woo files damage suit against SM | author =  | work = [[The Korea Times]] | date = 12 May 2015 | accessdate = 2016-04-20 | url = http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2016/04/135_178797.html }}</ref> No alleged that SM had also interfered with his career after he had left the company, and sought KR\u20a9100 million in damages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2018&no=95142|title=No Min-woo claimed against SM.|last=|first=|date=|work=mk.co.kr|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> No lost his lawsuit against SM Entertainment on July 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2016/07/21/no-min-woo-loses-lawsuit-sm-entertainment/|title=No Min Woo Loses Lawsuit Against SM Entertainment \u2013 Soompi|website=www.soompi.com}}</ref>\n\n====Huang Zitao====\nOn August 24, 2015, [[Tao (entertainer)|Tao]] became the third Chinese member of [[Exo (band)|EXO]] to file against SM and leave the group, being represented by the same legal team that represented former members Kris and Lu Han. On January 5, 2016, SM won one of its counter-lawsuits against Tao per the ruling of the Intermediate People's Court in Qingdao, China. The agency sued Tao over his failure to repay the company after his departure. They released an official statement saying, \"SM has ongoing lawsuits against EXO members Wu Yifan (Kris), Luhan, and Tao for violating their exclusive contracts and partaking in illegal promotions in China. Among these lawsuits, SM filed a lawsuit against Tao for failing to repay SM on October 13, 2015. An intermediate court in Qingdao, China made the verdict that Tao is to repay SM Entertainment as well as interest for the delayed payment.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/sm-entertainment-wins-lawsuit-against-tao-former-exo-member-responds-662117|title=SM Entertainment Wins Lawsuit Against Tao|work=International Business Times|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=416&aid=0000174747|title=SM, \uc5d1\uc18c \uc804 \uba64\ubc84 \ud0c0\uc624 \uc0c1\ub300 \ubd80\ub2f9\ud589\uc704 \uc18c\uc1a1 \uc2b9\uc18c|publisher=Naver|accessdate=2016-06-19|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===2009 MAMA Awards boycott===\nOn November 21, 2009, SM Entertainment boycotted the [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]] event, claiming reservations regarding the standard of fairness and the criteria used in [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s selections for award recipients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/11/201_55925.html |title=Music Awards Has Fresh Yet Disappointing Start |last=Han Sang |first=Hee |date=November 22, 2009 |newspaper=Korea Times |access-date=13 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125163015/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/11/201_55925.html |archive-date=25 November 2009 |df= }}</ref> The company specifically mentioned [[Girls' Generation]], who had topped Korean music charts for nine consecutive weeks and had won numerous awards for their single \"[[Tell Me Your Wish (Genie) (song)|Genie]]\", but had never won on Mnet's weekly [[M! Countdown]] show, and had only appeared on their charts a month after the album release. SM also cited the fact that voters had to pay a fee, saying that they \"did not want to see fans suffer any damage from the poll, which has commercial intentions.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009110321401713544|title=SM singers boycott Mnet music award|last=Kim|first=Jessica|date=3 November 2009|newspaper=Asiae|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Fair Trade Commission scrutiny===\nIn 2010, the [[Fair Trade Commission (South Korea)|Korea Fair Trade Commission]] (KFTC) undertook an investigation into SM Entertainment's policies, especially regarding artists' contract terms, and concluded that they were unfair. Artist contracts were subsequently reduced by a length of three years, and there was a reduction in the penalties for breach-of-contract violations. All the artists signed under SM at the time re-contracted with the agency under the new terms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?no=713677&year=2010|title=FTC, SM modified the contract of exclusive contract `recognition`|last=|first=|date=|work=mk.co.kr|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nSM was also one of fifteen companies sued and fined by the KFTC for [[Fair Trade Commission (South Korea)#2011 music price fixing scandal.5B1.5D|price rigging in 2011]].\n\nIn 2012, SM was accused of colluding with music distributors, but was cleared of the charge. On August 16, the Seoul High Court revealed their verdict on the issue: \"The KFTC has canceled all corrective orders against SM Entertainment, and the lawsuit costs will be paid by the defendant.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.hankooki.com/lpage/music/201208/sp2012081614244995510.htm|title=SM\uc5d4\ud130'\uc74c\uc6d0\uc720\ud1b5 \ub2f4\ud569' \uc624\uba85 \ubc97\uc5b4|date=16 August 2012|newspaper=Sports Hankooki|language=Korean|trans-title=SM Entertainment cleared of accusations of colluding with music distributors|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Red Velvet music video controversy===\nIn August 2014, after the release of [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]'s music video for \"[[Happiness (Red Velvet song)|Happiness]]\", Japanese media reported that images referencing the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]], as well as the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]], were seen in the background of the video. SM Entertainment responded to the reports, stating that \"after questioning the director, we found that he simply used a collage source for the images, and there was no intention behind it.\" The representative added, \"As SM wasn't able to catch it before, we will remove the material that caused the misunderstanding as soon as possible. We will make sure not to let this kind of thing happen in the future.\" SM later uploaded a new version of the music video without the controversial images.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnetamerica.com/news/article/72424/redvelvet-releases-mv-again|title=[Video] Red Velvet Re-Releases 'Happiness' MV with Edited Scenes|website=www.mnetamerica.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Pop music|South Korea}}\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.smtown.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to SM Entertainment\n|list=\n{{SM Entertainment}}\n{{SM Town}}\n{{K-pop}}\n{{KRX 100 companies}}\n{{Film distributors of South Korea}}\n{{Television production companies of South Korea}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:SM Entertainment]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Seoul]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on KOSDAQ]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music record labels]]\n[[Category:Event management companies of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Music production companies]]\n[[Category:Music publishing companies of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Soul music record labels]]\n[[Category:South Korean brands]]\n[[Category:South Korean record labels]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of South Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Sony Music Entertainment}}\n{{Short description|South Korean entertainment company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = SM Entertainment Co., Ltd.\n| native_name = \uc5d0\uc2a4.\uc5e0. \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8<br />SM \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| logo = SM Entertainment Logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type = Private\n| traded_as = {{kosdaq|041510}}<br />KRX 100 Component\n| founder = [[Lee Soo-man]]\n| key_people = Lee Sung-soo (CEO)<br />Tak Young-joon (CMO)<ref>{{cite web |title=SM\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8, \uc774\uc131\uc218\u00b7\ud0c1\uc601\uc900 \uacf5\ub3d9 \ub300\ud45c \uc774\uc0ac \uc120\uc784 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] |url=https://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=018&aid=0004594456 |website=entertain.naver.com |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |language=ko |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| industry = {{unbulleted list|[[Entertainment]]|[[Production company|production]]|[[retail]]|[[travel]]}}\n| genre = {{unbulleted list|[[K-pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Electropop]]|[[Electronic Dance Music|EDM]]|[[Experimental music]]}}\n| services = {{unbulleted list|Record Distribution | Licensing | Publishing}}\n| revenue = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{increase}} US$ 553.98 million (2019)|US$ 520 million (2018)|US$ 368 million (2017)|US$ 306 million (2016)|US$ 287 million (2015)}}\n| owner = (Shareholder Structure <ref>{{cite website|url=http://www.smentertainment.com/Investors/OperateInfo|title=IR Shareholder Structure|}}</ref>)<br />{{ubl|[[Lee Soo-man]] \u2013 18.73%|[[National Pension Service]] \u2013 9.02%|[[Korea Investment Management]] \u2013 7.64%|[[Korea Investment Value Asset Management]] \u2013 5.10%|[[Alibaba]] \u2013 3.71%|[[KB Asset Management]] \u2013 3.71%|others \u2013 52.09%}}\n| num_employees = 486 (2019)\n| divisions = {{unbulleted list|SM Entertainment Japan Inc. (2001)|SM Entertainment USA Inc. (2008)|SM Brand Marketing (2008)\n|SM F&B Development (2008)|SM Amusement (2008)|SM True Co., Ltd (2011)|Dream Maker Entertainment (2012)|SM Entertainment Beijing Co., Ltd (2012)|SM Mobile Communications (2015)|galaxiaSM (since 2015)|[[ESteem Entertainment|ESteem]] (since 2015)|[[Mystic Story]] (since 2017)|SM Planner (2017)|everysing (2017)|[[KeyEast|KEYEAST]] (since 2018)|[[Million Market]] (since 2018)|SM Entertainment Indonesia (since 2019)}}\n| subsid = {{unbulleted list|[[SM Culture & Contents]] (Since 2012)|[[Baljunso]] (Since 2014)|[[Label SJ]] (2015)|ScreaM Records (2016)|SM Life Design Group (Since 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0003031629|title=FNC, SM\uacfc \uc804\ub7b5\uc801 \uc81c\ud734\u2026'SM\ub77c\uc774\ud504\ub514\uc790\uc778\uadf8\ub8f9'\uc73c\ub85c \uc0ac\uba85 \ubcc0\uacbd(\uacf5\uc2dd)|publisher=}}</ref>}}\n| footnotes = \n| profit = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{increase}} US$ 44 million (2018)|US$ $26.5 million (2017)|US$ 21 million (2016)|US$ 19 million (2015)}}\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.smtown.com}}<br />{{URL|http://www.smentertainment.com/}}\n| caption = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1989}}<br />(as SM Studio)<br />{{start date and age|1995}}<br />(as SM Entertainment)\n| former_name = SM Studio (1989\u20131995)\n| location_city = [[Seoul]]\n| location_country = South Korea\n| locations = \n}}\n\n'''SM Entertainment Co., Ltd.''' ({{ko-hhrm|SM\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8}}) is South Korea's largest [[entertainment]] company,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=009&aid=0004115384|title=`\ubc30\uc6a9\uc900 \uc0ac\ub2e8` \ud488\uc740 SM, 1\uc870 \uc5d4\ud130\uacf5\ub8e1 \ub410\ub2e4|access-date=2018-11-19|language=ko}}</ref> founded in 1995 by [[Lee Soo-man]]. The company has developed and popularized numerous K-pop stars with huge global fandoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.donga.com/List/3/all/26/401789/1|title=: The big 3 of Korean pop music and entertainment:The DONG-A ILBO|website=english.donga.com|access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/07/31/koreas-s-m-entertainment-the-company-that-created-k-pop/|title=Korea's S.M. Entertainment: The Company That Created K-Pop|date=31 July 2013|work=Forbes|author=Forbes Staff}}</ref> SM is known for having led the global K-pop phenomenon and the musical side of \"Hallyu\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=144&aid=0000443747|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] SM \uc2a4\ud0c0 \ubc0f \uc9c1\uc6d0 350\uc5ec\uba85,\ud558\uc640\uc774\ub85c \ub300\uaddc\ubaa8 \ub2e8\ud569 \ub300\ud68c \ub5a0\ub09c\ub2e4\u2026\uac01\uc885 \ud654\uc81c, \uc9c4\ud48d\uacbd \uc787\ub530\ub77c|access-date=2018-11-19|language=ko}}</ref> also known as the \"[[Korean Wave]]\". Representative of the entertainment industry in Asia, the company operates its own comprehensive entertainment business including artist development, record label services, talent agency services, music production, music publishing, event management, and concert production.\n\nThe label is home to prominent [[K-pop]] artists such as [[Kangta]], [[S.E.S. (group)|S.E.S.]], [[BoA]], [[TVXQ!]], [[The Grace (group)|CSJH The Grace]], [[Super Junior]], [[Girls' Generation]], [[J-Min]], [[Shinee]], [[F(x) (group)|f(x)]], [[Zhou Mi (singer)|Zhou Mi]], [[Exo (band)|Exo]], [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]], [[NCT (band)|NCT]], and produced and popularized artists like [[H.O.T.]], [[Fly to the Sky]], [[Shinhwa]], [[TraxX]], and [[Henry Lau]]. It also manages a number of actors, including [[Kim Min-jong]] and [[Lee Yeon-hee]]. In Japan, SM Entertainment co-publishes [[Avex Trax]] releases for artists including [[Ayumi Hamasaki]], [[Namie Amuro]], and [[Koda Kumi]], as well as [[Johnny's Entertainment]] artists such as [[Arashi]] and [[KAT-TUN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smtown.com/link/jpop|title=SMTOWN J-POP ZONE|publisher=S.M. Entertainment}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, SM Entertainment had reported revenues of KR\u20a9325 billion (approximately US$287 million) and a net income of KR\u20a921.7 billion (US$19 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/q/is?s=041510.KQ&annual|title=041510.KQ Income Statement {{!}} S.M. Stock \u2013 Yahoo! UK & Ireland Finance|website=uk.finance.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1989\u20132000: Creation and first generation artists===\nAfter graduating from [[California State University, Northridge]] in the United States, [[Lee Soo-man]] returned to Korea and in 1989 established what was then known as \"SM Studio\" in the [[Apgujeong-dong|Apgujeong]] neighborhood of [[Gangnam District|Gangnam]], [[Seoul]]. In February 1995, the company changed its name to SM Entertainment and set up its capital fund.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Social Media Management: Value Chain and Business Models in Changing Media Markets|last1=Friedrichsen|last2=M\u00fchl-Benninghaus|first1=Mike|first2=Wolfgang|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2013|isbn=978-3-642-28896-8|location=Berlin|page=553}}</ref> SM then developed an in-house production system and created a string of successful artists, including boy band [[H.O.T.]] in 1996, girl group [[S.E.S. (group)|S.E.S.]] in 1997, boy band [[Shinhwa]] in 1998, R&B duo [[Fly to the Sky]] in 1999, and soloist [[BoA]] in 2000.\n\nJung Hae-ik was appointed [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] at the time of SM Entertainment's official reestablishment in 1995,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.daum.net/entertain/newsview?newsid=20130620093605651|title=\uc18c\ub144\uacf5\ud654\uad6d \"\uc774\ub984 \ub54c\ubb38\uc5d0 \ubd81\ud55c \uc544\uc774\ub3cc \uc544\ub2c8\ub0d0\ub354\ub77c\"|website=Daum \uc5f0\uc608|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref>  and was succeeded by Kim Kyung-wook in 1998.\n\n===2000\u20132005: Affiliations and second generation artists===\nThe early 2000s saw the disbandment of both H.O.T (in 2001) and S.E.S (in 2002).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20151111/74708087/1|title=SM Black History|last=|first=|date=2015-11-11|work=news.donga.com|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> Shinhwa departed to a new agency, and new acts like the duo [[Isak N Jiyeon]] and the boy band [[Black Beat]] failed to attain the popularity of previous SM artists.<ref name=\":0\" /> In December 2000, SM established an affiliate company called Fandango Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/157345|title=SM Entertainment merged with Fandango Korea|last=|first=|date=|work=No-Cut News|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko-KR}}</ref> In January 2001, the company founded an overseas division, SM Entertainment Japan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.etoday.co.kr/news/section/newsview.php?idxno=717254|title=Searching for entertainment industry power \u2461. SM entertainment|last=|first=|date=2013-04-12|work=\uc774\ud22c\ub370\uc774|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> Around the same time, the company was approved for listing on [[KOSDAQ]], and SM established an affiliation with the Japanese major label [[Avex Trax]]. SM also formed the subsidiaries BM Entertainment and Cid. K Entertainment (under which the girl groups [[M.I.L.K.]] and [[Shinvi]] were signed, respectively), but they later dissolved when their groups disbanded.\n\nIn late 2002, SM was awarded the Grand Prix of Ministry of Culture and Tourism for the Culture Contents for Export Award in music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://people.incruit.com/column/columnview.asp?bdno=100&colno=386929|title=Lee Soo-man SM Group Leader \u2013 Leader of popular culture industry moving entertainment industry|last=|first=|date=|website=people.incruit.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, SM became affiliated with Starlight Corporation Ltd. and C-Cube Entertainment Corporation. That same year, the company debuted five-member boy group [[TVXQ]]. The following years saw the debuts of artists such as [[TRAX (band)|TRAX]] (2004), [[The Grace (band)|The Grace]] (2005), and [[Super Junior]] (2005).\n\n===2005\u20132010: Expansion and international artists===\nIn 2005, Kim Young-min became the company's third CEO,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2016/03/386_192565.html|title=After 20 years, SM Entertainment to expand overseas base|date=2015-12-07|website=koreatimes|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> under whom several artists debuted with a view to promoting outside of South Korea. Artists produced by SM during this period included Chinese-born soloist [[Zhang Liyin]] (2006), Japanese-language soloist [[J-Min]] (2007), [[Girls' Generation]] (2007), [[Shinee]] (2008), and [[F(x) (band)|f(x)]] (2009). In April 2008, SM debuted a Mandarin-language sub-unit of Super Junior, named [[Super Junior-M]]. In October 2008, SM announced plans for BoA's debut in the American market, under a newly formed subsidiary label named SM Entertainment USA.\n\nIn May 2008, the SM Art Company opened under co-CEO Pyo In-bong, with a focus on producing theatrical works. The company's first venture was a production of the American musical comedy [[Xanadu (musical)|''Xanadu'']], starring Super Junior members [[Heechul]] and [[Kangin]].<ref>Koh Young-aah [http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20080530000048 \"Super Junior members set to make move into musicals\"] ''Korea Herald''. 30 May 2008. Retrieved 3 April 2012.</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132012: Joint and further ventures===\n{{see also|SM Culture & Contents}}\nIn February 2010, after two decades on SM Entertainment's board of directors, founder Lee Soo-man resigned from his position in order to \"focus more energy on SM's overseas business, new business management, and artist development.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010022514424957673|title=Lee Soo-man steps down from SM board of directors|last=Kun-ouc|first=Park|date=25 February 2010|newspaper=10 Asia|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> In March of the same year, [[KMP Holdings]] was established as a joint venture between SM Entertainment, [[YG Entertainment]], [[JYP Entertainment]], [[Star Empire Entertainment|Star Empire]], Medialine, CAN Entertainment, and Music Factory.<ref>[http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?sc=30000019&cm=%EC%A6%9D%EA%B6%8C%20%EC%A3%BC%EC%9A%94%EA%B8%B0%EC%82%AC&year=2010&no=138710&selFlag=&relatedcode=&wonNo=&sID=502 \"Korean Music Power: KMP Holdings Co. Ltd. Launched!\"] ''[[Maeil Kyungje]]''. 18 March 2010. Retrieved 2012-10-06 {{in lang|ko}}</ref> The firm's first release from SM was Super Junior's fifth studio album, ''[[Mr. Simple]]'', which marked the end of SM's self-distribution. In May, SM announced its highest ever first quarter operating profits, at KR{{SK won|10.4&nbsp;billion}}, up 471% from the same period the previous year. Gross revenue was reported at KR{{SK won|22.7&nbsp;billion}}, a 58% increase on the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010051314034381443|title=SM Entertainment records biggest Q1 profit|last=Kim|first=Lynn|date=13 May 2010|newspaper=10 Asia|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, SM Entertainment, YG Entertainment, JYP Entertainment, KeyEast, AMENT, and Star J Entertainment came together to form United Asia Management, a joint investment agency geared towards advancing Asian music worldwide. That August, SM joined with Thai media company [[TrueVisions]] to create an international joint venture, SM True.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=109&aid=0002241539|title=SM \uc5d4\ud130, \ud0dc\uad6d\uc11c \uccab \ud574\uc678 \ud569\uc791\ubc95\uc778 'SM True' \uc124\ub9bd|date=17 August 2011|newspaper=Naver News|language=Korean|trans-title=SM Entertainment establishes joint venture company with Thailand\u2019s True Visions Group, \u2018SM True\u2019|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Super_Junior_performs_at_the_MTV_EXIT_Hanoi_Concert_2010.jpg|thumb|[[Super Junior]] at the MTV Exit Hanoi Concert in 2010.]]\nIn 2012, SM debuted the large-scale boy group [[Exo (band)|EXO]], split into two units in order to promote in Korea and China simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20120127n03950?mid=e0101|title=SM \uc0c8 \uadf8\ub8f9 EXO, 30\uc77c \ud504\ub864\ub85c\uadf8 \uc2f1\uae00 \uacf5\uac1c|website=\ub124\uc774\ud2b8\ub274\uc2a4|language=ko-KR|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref> In February, SM acquired Hawaiian travel firm Happy Hawaii and launched SMTown Travel, a new business initiative specializing in travel and tourism under Kang Jung-hyun.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stviewEng.php?type=3&no=2012022714534028406|title=SM Entertainment takes over travel agency|last=Mun|first=Wan-Sik|date=27 February 2012|newspaper=Star News|access-date=1 May 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824075531/http://star.mt.co.kr/stviewEng.php?type=3&no=2012022714534028406|archive-date=24 August 2012|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smtowntravel.com/|title=SM Global Package On Sale!|website=www.smtowntravel.com|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref> Later that year, SMTown Travel offered package deals for overseas fans attending Super Junior's ''[[Super Show 4 Tour]]'' encore concerts in Seoul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=5801|title=Super Junior to Hold Encore Concert in Seoul in May|last=Ho|first=Stewart|date=23 April 2012|publisher=CJ E&M|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref> In March, 47 of SM Entertainment's recording artists became stockholders of the company. Kangta, BoA, and most members of Super Junior and Girls\u2019 Generation received 680 shares each (with a value of approximately US$27,200 per person), while members of more recent groups like Shinee and f(x) received 340 shares each (with a value of around US$13,600 per person).<ref>Kim, JiYeon [http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201203271706_4801&nowPage=4 \"SM Artists Take on SM Stock\"] ''Mnet News''. 27 March 2012. Retrieved 30 March 2012.</ref> In August, SM held an art exhibition at the [[COEX Convention & Exhibition Center]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2957706|title=Fantasies come true at the high-tech SM ART exhibit|last=Kim|first=Hyung-eun|date=10 August 2012|newspaper=Joongang Daily|access-date=6 October 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126203405/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2957706|archive-date=26 January 2013|df=}}</ref> and collaborated with Visa and KB Kookmin Card to begin printing SM artist cards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://media.daum.net/culture/others/newsview?newsid=20120726091412600|title=SM \uccb4\ud06c\uce74\ub4dc \ub098\uc628\ub2e4, VISA-KB\uad6d\ubbfc\uce74\ub4dc\uc640 MOU\uccb4\uacb0|date=26 July 2012|newspaper=Daum|language=Korean|trans-title=SM Entertainment to make MOU contract with VISA and KB Card|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> That same month, Korean TV personalities [[Kang Ho-dong]] and [[Shin Dong-yup (entertainer)|Shin Dong-yup]] announced that they had signed exclusive contracts with SM's new broadcasting subsidiary, [[S.M. Culture & Contents|SM Culture & Contents]] (SM C&C), marking SM's expansion into television.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=12644|title=Kang Ho Dong Announces Return by Signing with SM C&C|last=Lee|first=JinHo|date=17 August 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=12700|title=Three Reasons Why Kang Ho Dong Signed with SM|last=Choi|first=Eunhwa|date=18 August 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> The next month, in September, SM C&C merged with AM Entertainment (which then represented top actors such as [[Jang Dong-gun]], [[Kim Ha-neul]], and [[Han Ji-min]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=15384|title=SM C&C Takes Over AM Entertainment \u2013 Home to Jang Dong Gun, Kim Ha Neul and Others|last=Ho|first=Stewart|date=19 September 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> and two other TV personalities, [[Lee Su-geun]] and [[Kim Byung-man]], announced that they had also signed with SM.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=15399|title=Lee Su Geun, Kim Byung Man Join Kang Ho Dong at SM C&C?|last=Ho|first=Stewart|date=19 September 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> In November, KMP Holdings was acquired by [[KT Corporation|KT Music]], and in June 2013, KT Music absorbed KMP's distribution network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kt.com/eng/pr/news_01_view.jsp|title=(kt PR room) KT to acquire KMP Holdings to strengthen its music businesses|date=November 23, 2012|publisher=[[KT Corporation]]|accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u2013present: Third generation artists and ScreaM Records===\n{{see also|SM Rookies|Label SJ|SM Station}}\n[[File:Smentertainment_logo.jpg|thumb|Company logo until October 2017]]\nIn 2013, SM C&C acquired Hoon Media (a production company led by Lee Hoon-hee, responsible for KBS serials ''[[1 vs. 100#International variants|1 vs 100]]'', ''[[Heroine 6|Heroines 6]]'', ''[[Qualifications of Men]]'', and ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'') and [[Woollim Entertainment]], a record label responsible for artists such as [[Infinite (band)|Infinite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpopasia.com/news/sm-entertainment-acquires-woollim-entertainment-creates-new-sublabel::14629.html|title=SM Entertainment Acquires Woollim Entertainment, Creates New Sublabel|last=Aysohmay|first=|date=9 August 2013|website=Jpopasia|publisher=Jpopasia|access-date=20 April 2016}}</ref> In January 2014, SM and the other six talent agencies behind [[KMP Holdings]] formed a collective bond partnership and bought 13.48% of [[KT Music]]'s stocks, leaving parent [[KT Corporation]] with 49.99%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/news/news_view.php?f_seq=103&sgenre=issue |title=SM, YG, JYP lead 7 companies as KT Music's new stakeholders |author=Cho Seung-hoon |date=January 24, 2014 |work=[[Gaon Music Chart]] |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association. |access-date=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006080320/http://gaonchart.co.kr/news/news_view.php?f_seq=103&sgenre=issue |archive-date= 6 October 2014 |df= }}</ref> In February, SM acquired a share in [[Baljunso]], an indie record label founded in 1991 by Kang Byung-yong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/59613/sm-invests-in-indie-label|title=KPOP NEWS \u2013 SM Entertainment Invests in Indie Label Baljunso to Spotlight Nonmainstream Music {{!}} Mwave|website=mwave.interest.me|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> On August 1, SM debuted [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]], its first girl group since f(x) five years prior.\n\nIn August 2015, SM partnered with sports marketing company IB Worldwide to create Galaxia SM, responsible for golfer [[Inbee Park|Park In-bee]], gymnast [[Son Yeon-jae]], and [[Shin-Soo Choo|Choo Shin-soo]], right fielder for the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].<ref>''[[Korea Times]]'': [http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/08/201_185635.html SM, IB Worldwide ink deal to create 'sportainment']</ref> On November 6, the 10th anniversary of [[Super Junior]]'s debut, SM announced the creation of the group's own sub-label, [[Label SJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/99582/exclusive-super-junior-label-lable-sj-established-for-10-year-anniversary|title=KPOP NEWS \u2013 Exclusive Super Junior Label \u2032Lable SJ\u2032 &#91;sic&#93; Established for 10th Anniversary|website=Mwave|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> In late 2015, SM partnered with modeling company ESteem to promote self-owned content and network.[[SM Entertainment#cite note-38|<sup>[38]</sup>]] The venture later expanded its acting division through the acting debuts of models Ki Do-hoon and Lee Cheol-woo.oo.\n\nIn January 2016, founder Lee Soo-man held a conference at the SM Coex Artium, announcing plans for a new boy group, [[NCT (band)|NCT]] (Neo Culture Technology), with \"unlimited members\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201601271758282555044_2|title=SM Entertainment\u2019s next boy band to have 'unlimited' members|website=kpopherald.koreaherald.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/korea-firm-unveils-k-pop-band-limitless-members-104640224--finance.html?ref=gs|title=S. Korea firm unveils K-pop band with limitless members|website=www.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> The first unit of this group, NCT U, released its first two singles in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2016/04/386_201890.html|title=SM's new K-pop band NCT U to debut this week|date=2016-04-04|website=koreatimes|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> NCT has since expanded to three more units - the South Korea-based fixed unit [[NCT 127]] in July 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hype.my/2016/113666/nct127-sm-entertainment-unveils-members-of-new-nct-sub-unit/|title=(UPDATE) #NCT127: SM Entertainment Unveils Members Of New NCT Sub-Unit|website=Hype|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> the youth/teen-aged unit [[NCT Dream]] in August 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/music/now/read?oid=108&aid=0002548916|title=NCT DREAM, \ub370\ubdd4\uace1 '\uce04\uc789\uac80' 25\uc77c '\uc5e0\uce74'\uc11c \uccab\uc120|date=August 19, 2016|website=Naver|publisher=Star Money|language=ko}}</ref> and the China-based [[WayV]] in January 2019.<ref name=\"WayV\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2019/01/16/wayv-represents-sm-entertainments-goals-for-global-dominance-through-cultural-technology/|title=WayV Represents SM Entertainment's Goals For Global Dominance Through Cultural Technology|last=Herman|first=Tamar|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> WayV is being managed by their own sub-label, Label V.<ref name=\"WayV\" />\n\nAt the beginning of the year, the company opened a restaurant, SMT Seoul,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pulsenews.co.kr/view.php?sc=30800022&year=2016&no=59733|title=SM Entertainment opens up-scale restaurant SMT Seoul \u2013 Pulse by Maeil Business News Korea|website=pulsenews.co.kr|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> and also established a series of stores selling branded foods under the name SUM Market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.joins.com/article/19582509|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] SM\uc5d4\ud130, \ubcf8\uc0ac\uc5d0 \u2018\uc5d1\uc18c \ud3b8\uc758\uc810\u2019 \uc5f0\ub2e4\u2026\uc9c0\ub09c\ud574 \ub9d0 \uc774\uc218\ub9cc-\uc815\uc6a9\uc9c4 \ub9cc\ub098 \ubc11\uadf8\ub9bc|date=2016-02-17|website=news.joins.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> On February 11, 2016, the Chinese e-commerce giant [[Alibaba Group]] acquired a 4 percent minority stake in SM Entertainment for US$30 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kang|first1=John|title=Why Alibaba Bought $30M Stake In K-Pop Giant SM Entertainment, Home To EXO And Girls' Generation|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johnkang/2016/02/11/why-alibaba-bought-30m-stake-in-k-pop-giant-sm-entertainment-home-to-exo-and-girls-generation/#7e130efda556|work=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, SM released the first single under its newly established [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] label ScreaM Records, \"Wave\", featuring [[F(x) (band)|f(x)]] members Amber and Luna and produced by Xavi & Gi and E-mart's Electro Mart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160426000798|title=SM\u2019s EDM label to drop first track|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=109&aid=0003305800|title=SM, EDM\ub808\uc774\ube14 'ScreaM Records' \uc124\ub9bd..5\uc6d46\uc77c \uccab\uace1 \ubc1c\ud45c|website=Naver|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> ScreaM Records opened as part of SM's New Culture Technology 2016 project, under which SM also initiated the digital music channel [[SM Station]] and a number of mobile apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreadailyus.com/introducing-nct-how-sm-entertainment-is-taking-advantage-of-digital-platforms-to-take-over-the-global-entertainment-market/|title=Introducing NCT: How SM Entertainment is taking advantage of digital platforms to take over the global entertainment market|last=Yi|first=Lily|website=www.koreadailyus.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> In late 2016, SM began organizing a ''[[League of Legends]]'' tournament called  SM Super Celeb League, in which SM artists [[Heechul]] and [[Byun Baek-hyun|Baekhyun]] played against both professional gamers and fans from South Korea and China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.inven.co.kr/webzine/news/?news=166742&iskin=esports|title='\uae40\ud76c\ucca0-\ubc31\ud604' \ucc38\uc5ec! \ud32c\uacfc \ud568\uaed8 \ud558\ub294 \uc911\uad6d LoL \uc774\ubca4\ud2b8\uc804|website=inven.co.kr|date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2017, a source from the task force in charge of the ''international K-pop academy'' has plans to open this upcoming September. The Gangnam-based academy is a collaborative venture with the private Jongro Sky Academy. Plans for the school to be certified as an alternative program for domestic Korean middle and high school education, as well as US secondary school education, are also underway.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insight.co.kr/newsRead.php?ArtNo=94073|title=SM, \uc62c\ud574 9\uc6d4 \uac15\ub0a8 \ud55c\ubcf5\ud310\uc5d0 'K\ud31d \uad6d\uc81c\ud559\uad50' \uac1c\uad50\ud55c\ub2e4|website=insight.co.kr|date=February 16, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, SM acquired the independent record label [[Mystic Entertainment]], becoming the label's largest shareholder.<ref>[http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002602163] star.mt 2017/03</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, SM opened its Indonesian office in Jakarta.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.viva.co.id/showbiz/gosip/1118974-5-spot-foto-lucu-di-kantor-sm-entertainment-jakarta|title=5 Spot Foto Lucu di Kantor SM Entertainment Jakarta|date=2019-02-08|website=VIVA.co.id|access-date=2019-09-08|language=Indonesian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jawapos.com/entertainment/music-movie/08/02/2019/ada-kantor-cabang-sm-entertainment-di-indonesia-bakal-gelar-audisi/|title=Ada Kantor Cabang, SM Entertainment di Indonesia Bakal Gelar Audisi|date=2019-02-08|website=[[Jawa Pos|JawaPos.com]]|access-date=2019-09-08|language=Indonesian|editor1-last=Purnamasari|editor1-first=Deti Mega}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2019, SM and [[Capitol Music Group]] \u2013 which earlier signed NCT 127 in April 2019<ref name=\"Capitol\">{{cite web|last1=Cirisano|first1=Tatiana|title=Capitol Music Group & Caroline Sign K-Pop Stars NCT 127 to Distribution Deal|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8505641/nct-127-capitol-music-group-caroline-distribution-deal|website=[[billboard]]|accessdate=April 5, 2019|date=April 4, 2019}}</ref> \u2013 announced [[SuperM]], a [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] consisting of [[Lee Tae-min|Taemin]] from Shinee, [[Byun Baek-hyun|Baekhyun]] and [[Kai (entertainer, born 1994)|Kai]] from Exo, and [[Lee Tae-yong|Taeyong]], [[Ten (singer)|Ten]], [[Lucas Wong|Lucas]] and [[Mark Lee (singer)|Mark]] from NCT units NCT 127, NCT Dream and WayV, in the 2019 Capitol Congress event in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"SuperM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/08/07/super-m-the-avengers-of-k-pop-unveiled-by-sm-entertainment-and-capitol-music-group/ |title=Super M, 'The Avengers Of K-Pop,' Unveiled By SM Entertainment And Capitol Music Group |last=Benjamin |first=Jeff |date=August 7, 2019 |website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |publisher= |access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref> The group debuted in October 2019.<ref name=\"SuperM\" />\n\nIn November 2019, SM Entertainment signed with [[Creative Artists Agency]] for representation in all areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/k-pop-powerhouse-sm-entertainment-home-to-nct-127-superm-and-exo-inks-with-caa-1203392415/ |title=K-Pop Powerhouse SM Entertainment, Home to NCT 127, SuperM and EXO, Inks With CAA |last=Kim |first=Jae-Ha |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher= |access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries==\nSource:<ref name=\"GROUP COMPANIES\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smentertainment.com/Overview/Affiliate|title=SM Entertainment GROUP COMPANIES |publisher=SM Entertainment|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[SM Culture & Contents|SM C&C]] (2012)\n* Dream Maker Entertainment\n* SM Life Design Group Co., Ltd (2018)\n* SM True (2011)\n* SM Brand Marketing (2008)\n* Everysing (2017)\n* Galaxia SM (2004)\n* [[Million Market]] (2018)\n* SM Japan (2001)\n* [[KeyEast]] (2018)\n* SM USA (2008)\n* SM F&B Development (2008)\n* SM TOWN Planner (2017)\n* [[ESteem Entertainment|ESteem]] (2015)\n* [[Mystic Story]] (2017)\n\n==Artists==\n{{main|SM Town|SM Entertainment artists}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|SM Entertainment discography}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|SM Culture & Contents#Filmography}}\n\n==Controversies==\n===Contractual disputes===\n====JYJ (TVXQ)====\nIn late July 2009, three of the five original members of SM Entertainment boy group [[TVXQ]] \u2013 [[Kim Jaejoong]], [[Park Yoochun]], and [[Kim Junsu]] \u2013 applied to the Seoul Central District Court to investigate the validity of their contract with SM,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/08/178_49459.html|title=TVXQ Feuds With SM Entertainment|date=2009-08-02|work=The Korea Times|accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10167 |title=Is TVXQ Headed for Breakup? |date=2009-08-03 |work=KBS World |access-date=3 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105210213/http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10167 |archive-date=5 January 2010 |df= }}</ref> as they felt the thirteen-year contract was excessively long and that earnings were not fairly distributed to the members,<ref name=\"lawsuit2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/08/178_49540.html|title=TVXQ to Stick Together Despite Legal Dispute|date=2009-08-03|work=The Korea Times|accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref> but contract destruction, they shall be compensated to the Employer by three times the total investment amount and two times the ordinary profit during the remaining contract period.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/08/04/2009080401107.html|title=TVXQ is a 'slave contract' ... SM, 'quasi-fraud'|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> The news of this dispute caused SM Entertainment's [[KOSPI]] stock price to drop by 10.06%.<ref>Thomson Reuters. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090806092540/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2009/08/03/afx6730465.html Korea Hot Stocks \u2013 Hankook Tire, SM Ent, Ssangyong Motor]. ''[[Forbes.com]]''. August 3, 2009. Retrieved 3 August 2009.</ref> In addition, 120,000 fans of TVXQ filed a petition against SM's long-term contracts to the Seoul Central District Court, and also filed for compensation for an SMTown Live Concert that was canceled a week before its scheduled date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10351 |title=TVXQ Fan Club Files for Compensation for Cancelled Concert |date=2009-09-03 |work=KBS World |access-date=3 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030203834/http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10351 |archive-date=30 October 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\nTheir statement read, \"(They) have had health problems and finally reached their physical limits, but SM Entertainment continued to send them abroad and plan excessive activities. Thus, the three members have started to hope they will be able to continue their careers as they wish, instead of being used as tools for the agency's profits.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sang-hee|first1=Han|title=TVXQ to Stick Together Despite Legal Dispute|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/08/178_49540.html|website=The Korea Times|publisher=The Korea Times Co.|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe court ruled in the favour of the three ex-members. In response, SM held a press conference claiming that the lawsuit was fraudulent, and filed an injunction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=10760|title=SM Entertainment Calls the TVXQ Suit a Big Fraud|date=2009-11-02|work=KBS World|accessdate=2 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/02/18/2011021801086.html|title=JYJ Win Legal Battle with Former Management|date=18 February 2011|work=Chosun Ilbo|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref> In early May 2010, it was announced that Jaejoong, Yoochun, and Junsu would return to the stage as [[JYJ]] under a new management agency, [[C-JeS Entertainment]].<ref>[http://kr.news.yahoo.com/service/news/shellview.htm?articleid=2010052010224117308&linkid=4&newssetid=1352 \"\uc2dc\uc544\uc900\uc218 \ub4f1 \ub3d9\ubc29\uc2e0\uae30 3\uc778, \uc0c8 \uadf8\ub8f9 \uc774\ub984\uc740 J.Y.J?\"] ''Yahoo News''. 20 May 2010. Retrieved 2012-10-06 {{in lang|ko}}</ref> The injunction was dismissed by the Seoul Central District Court on February 17, 2011, and the final decision on the case was postponed indefinitely for mediation under the justice department.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/02/18/2011021801086.html|title=JYJ Win Legal Battle with Former Management|work=Chosun Ilbo|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=15363|title=Decision on JYJ vs. SM Entertainment Case Postponed Indefinitely for Mediation|last=Park|first=HyunMin|date=19 September 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 2012, during a voluntary arbitration at the Seoul Central District Court, SM Entertainment and JYJ reached a mutual agreement to terminate all contracts between the two parties and not to interfere with each other's activities in the future, concluding the lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2963083|title=JYJ and SM finally reach agreement|last=Sunwoo|first=Carla|date=29 November 2012|newspaper=Joongang Daily|access-date=5 December 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130111053417/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2963083|archive-date=11 January 2013|df=}}</ref> SM reportedly stated that they had decided to end the litigation \"to avoid bringing additional harm to U-Know Yunho and Max Changmin, who are active as TVXQ, and to avoid making any more unneeded issues.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=22343|title=SM and JYJ Put an End to Their Long, Winding Legal Suit|date=28 November 2012|newspaper=enewsWorld|agency=CJ E&M|accessdate=5 December 2012|author=Park, HyunMin|author2=Erika Kim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2012112813495846832|title=JYJ, SM Come to Agreement Regarding Exclusive Contract Issue|last=Lee|first=Tae Ho|date=28 November 2012|newspaper=10 Asia|accessdate=5 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Han Geng====\nOn December 21, 2009, five months after the three former TVXQ members filed their lawsuit and while the dispute was still active, [[Han Geng]], the only Chinese member of [[Super Junior]], also filed a lawsuit against SM. Han Geng filed for similar reasons: unfair profit distribution, and an unfair thirteen-year contract that contained provisions in SM's favor that he was not allowed to revise or end.<ref>[http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2009122215270135930&type=1&outlink=1 \"\ud55c\uacbd \"SM, \u975e\uc815\uc0c1\uc801 \ud65c\ub3d9\uac15\uc694\"] ''Star News''. 22 December 2009. Retrieved 2012-05-01 {{in lang|ko}}</ref> The artist's friend and later manager Sun Le also submitted a statement to the Korean courts citing SM Entertainment's violation of Han Geng's rights, which was later leaked via the internet.<ref>[http://community.livejournal.com/geng_bao/76937.html#cutid1 \"Exclusive Interview with Han Geng's Team\"] (In Chinese with English Translation) ''Beijing Youth Weekly Magazine'' 25 August 2010. Retrieved 1 May 2012.</ref> The statement argued that SM had discriminated against Han Geng financially as well as in terms of management.\n\nOn September 27, 2011, Han Geng's departure from Super Junior was made official when legal representatives of both Han Geng and SM released a joint statement saying that \"Han Geng and SM Entertainment have amicably settled on a mutual agreement, and the lawsuit was able to come to a close after Han Geng submitted his 'Notice of Withdrawal of Appeal.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=382&aid=0000011661|title=SM Entertainment's official position: Han Geng has \"come to a mutual agreement, and will terminate proceedings\"|date=September 2011|publisher=news.naver.com|accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?a_id=2011092711070333667 |title=Han Geng's official position: \"SM Entertainment has amicably agreed\" |date=September 2011 |publisher=10asia.co.kr |access-date=10 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017220337/http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?a_id=2011092711070333667 |archive-date=17 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n====Kris Wu====\nOn May 15, 2014, [[Kris Wu]], a Chinese-Canadian member of [[Exo (band)|EXO]], filed a lawsuit to terminate his contract with SM, as first reported by Chinese news portal Sina.<ref name=\"ent.sina.com.cn2\">{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/y/k/2014-05-15/09314141917.shtml|title=EXO-M\u961f\u957f\u5434\u4ea6\u51e1\u63d0\u51fa\u89e3\u7ea6 SM\u518d\u9677\u89e3\u7ea6\u95e8|work=sina.com.cn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140515000936|title=EXO-M\u2019s Kris sues SM to end exclusive contract|author=The Korea Herald|work=koreaherald.com}}</ref> He was represented by Cho Bum-suk, the same lawyer that handled [[Han Geng]]'s case. Kris, whose real name is Wu Yifan, was quoted as saying, \"The company has treated me like a machine part or as an object of control rather than presenting a vision as an entertainer.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Phillip |title=SM Entertainment\u2019s lawsuit history over \u2018unfair contracts\u2019 |url=http://www.hellokpop.com/news/sm-entertainments-lawsuit-history-over-unfair-contracts/ |website=HelloKpop |publisher=hellokpop.com |accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> He left the group in the same month that the lawsuit was made public, while the rest of the group continued to promote their single \"Overdose.\" On July 21, 2016, Kris officially parted ways with EXO, although his contract with SM remains valid until 2022.<ref name=\"LuKrisConclu\">{{cite web|last1=Alexander|first1=Kevin|title=Kris And Luhan's Contract Lawsuit Against SM Entertainment Ends|url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/273224/20160722/sm-entertainment-lawsuit-kris-luhan-sue-end-conclusion-negotiation-contract.htm|website=KPOPStarz|accessdate=23 July 2016|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Jessica Jung====\nOn September 29, 2014, [[Girls' Generation]] member [[Jessica Jung]] claimed in a [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]] post that she had been forced out of the group, writing:<blockquote>''I was excited about our upcoming fan events only to shockingly be informed by my company and 8 others that as of today, I'm no longer a member. I'm devastated \u2013 my priority and love is to serve as a member of GG, but for no justifiable reason, I am being forced out''.<ref>[http://www.weibo.com/3547642417/Bpknsn8y8 Jung's Weibo update on September 30, 2014] weibo.com (September 30, 2014). Retrieved 30 September 2014.</ref></blockquote>The following day, Jung released a statement claiming that in August 2014 her fellow group members and SM had been positive about the launch of her fashion business, Blanc and Eclare. As of early September, she claimed, they had all changed their stance, and she was directed to either close the business or cease promotions as a member of Girls' Generation. She claimed to have received the day before a \"one-sided notice\" asking her to leave the group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/v/1e23e60b787c4ff4b3f63162baa02eff|title=Jessica's exits Girl's Generation|last=|first=|date=2014-09-30|work=\ud55c\uad6d\uc77c\ubcf4|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nHowever, according to SM, Jung had unilaterally informed them in early spring that she would leave the group after one more album. But before agreements could be made, she had set up her independent business, which caused problems for the group's professional schedules. This prompted management to begin promoting Girls' Generation as eight members rather than nine, with the intention of announcing the news; however, Jung had already \"posted her own perspective\u201d. The company then stated that the group would henceforth continue as eight, while they would still manage Jung's individual schedule.<ref>[http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/77155/sm-makes-official-statement-on-jessica SM States that SNSD will Promote as Eight Without Jessica] CJ E&M enewsWorld (September 30, 2014). Retrieved 23 February 2016.</ref> In the days immediately after this news came to light, company stocks dropped by KR\u20a93,350 per share, from KR\u20a940,750 to KR\u20a937,400, losing SM a total of KR\u20a969 billion (approximately US$65&nbsp;million).{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nOn August 6, 2015, Jung and SM Entertainment reached an agreement to terminate her contract, with Jung stating, \"This release is to confirm that SM Entertainment ('SM') and I have officially parted ways. I will cherish the many years we spent and I wish SM the best of luck in all of its endeavors.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=kiddy_days|title=Former Girls\u2019 Generation Member Jessica Officially Leaves SM Entertainment|url=https://www.soompi.com/2015/08/05/former-girls-generation-member-jessica-officially-leaves-sm-entertainment/|website=Soompi|publisher=Viki Inc.|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Lu Han====\nOn October 10, 2014, [[Luhan (singer)|Lu Han]] became the second Chinese member of [[Exo (band)|EXO]] to file to nullify his contract with SM Entertainment and leave the group, just over four months after Kris had done the same.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=581895|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \ub8e8\ud55c, SM\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\uc5d0 \uc18c\uc1a1\u2026\ud06c\ub9ac\uc2a4 \ub4a4 \uc787\ub098|website=TV\ub9ac\ud3ec\ud2b8|language=ko-KR|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201410101029561131&ext=na|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \ub8e8\ud55c, SM\uc5d0 \uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d \ud574\uc9c0\uc18c\uc1a1\u2026\ud06c\ub9ac\uc2a4\uc640 \uac19\uc740 \ud589\ubcf4|website=www.mydaily.co.kr|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201410101325541210|title=SM \"\ub8e8\ud55c \uac11\uc791\uc2a4\ub7f0 \uc18c\uc1a1 \ub2f9\ud639, \ubc30\ud6c4\uc138\ub825 \uc758\uc2ec\ub41c\ub2e4\" \uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5|website=www.newsen.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> His lawsuit included the claim that SM had favored the Korean sub-unit EXO-K over the Chinese sub-unit EXO-M. Within 15 minutes of the announcement, company stocks had dropped by 9.41%, from KR\u20a937,000 to KR\u20a933,250 per share.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} The stock's worth contracted by 15%, hitting the maximum decrease in price KOSDAQ allows for a day, and falling to a more-than-one-year low.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2014/10/10/exo-member-luhan-files-lawsuit-to-leave-k-pop-group/|title=EXO Member Luhan Files Lawsuit To Leave K-Pop Group|last=Lee|first=Min-Jeong|date=10 October 2014|website=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> On July 21, 2016, Lu Han officially parted ways with EXO, although his contract with SM remains valid until 2022.<ref name=\"LuKrisConclu\" />\n\n====No Min-woo====\nIn April 2015, [[No Min-woo]], a former member of [[TraxX|TRAX]], filed a lawsuit against SM for subjecting him to an unlawful seventeen-year contract.<ref name=\"culture line\">{{cite web | title = No Min-woo files damage suit against SM | author =  | work = [[The Korea Times]] | date = 12 May 2015 | accessdate = 2016-04-20 | url = http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2016/04/135_178797.html }}</ref> No alleged that SM had also interfered with his career after he had left the company, and sought KR\u20a9100 million in damages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2018&no=95142|title=No Min-woo claimed against SM.|last=|first=|date=|work=mk.co.kr|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref> No lost his lawsuit against SM Entertainment on July 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2016/07/21/no-min-woo-loses-lawsuit-sm-entertainment/|title=No Min Woo Loses Lawsuit Against SM Entertainment \u2013 Soompi|website=www.soompi.com}}</ref>\n\n====Huang Zitao====\nOn August 24, 2015, [[Tao (entertainer)|Tao]] became the third Chinese member of [[Exo (band)|EXO]] to file against SM and leave the group, being represented by the same legal team that represented former members Kris and Lu Han. On January 5, 2016, SM won one of its counter-lawsuits against Tao per the ruling of the Intermediate People's Court in Qingdao, China. The agency sued Tao over his failure to repay the company after his departure. They released an official statement saying, \"SM has ongoing lawsuits against EXO members Wu Yifan (Kris), Luhan, and Tao for violating their exclusive contracts and partaking in illegal promotions in China. Among these lawsuits, SM filed a lawsuit against Tao for failing to repay SM on October 13, 2015. An intermediate court in Qingdao, China made the verdict that Tao is to repay SM Entertainment as well as interest for the delayed payment.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/sm-entertainment-wins-lawsuit-against-tao-former-exo-member-responds-662117|title=SM Entertainment Wins Lawsuit Against Tao|work=International Business Times|accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=416&aid=0000174747|title=SM, \uc5d1\uc18c \uc804 \uba64\ubc84 \ud0c0\uc624 \uc0c1\ub300 \ubd80\ub2f9\ud589\uc704 \uc18c\uc1a1 \uc2b9\uc18c|publisher=Naver|accessdate=2016-06-19|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===2009 MAMA Awards boycott===\nOn November 21, 2009, SM Entertainment boycotted the [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]] event, claiming reservations regarding the standard of fairness and the criteria used in [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s selections for award recipients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/11/201_55925.html |title=Music Awards Has Fresh Yet Disappointing Start |last=Han Sang |first=Hee |date=November 22, 2009 |newspaper=Korea Times |access-date=13 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125163015/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/11/201_55925.html |archive-date=25 November 2009 |df= }}</ref> The company specifically mentioned [[Girls' Generation]], who had topped Korean music charts for nine consecutive weeks and had won numerous awards for their single \"[[Tell Me Your Wish (Genie) (song)|Genie]]\", but had never won on Mnet's weekly [[M! Countdown]] show, and had only appeared on their charts a month after the album release. SM also cited the fact that voters had to pay a fee, saying that they \"did not want to see fans suffer any damage from the poll, which has commercial intentions.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009110321401713544|title=SM singers boycott Mnet music award|last=Kim|first=Jessica|date=3 November 2009|newspaper=Asiae|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Fair Trade Commission scrutiny===\nIn 2010, the [[Fair Trade Commission (South Korea)|Korea Fair Trade Commission]] (KFTC) undertook an investigation into SM Entertainment's policies, especially regarding artists' contract terms, and concluded that they were unfair. Artist contracts were subsequently reduced by a length of three years, and there was a reduction in the penalties for breach-of-contract violations. All the artists signed under SM at the time re-contracted with the agency under the new terms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?no=713677&year=2010|title=FTC, SM modified the contract of exclusive contract `recognition`|last=|first=|date=|work=mk.co.kr|access-date=2018-05-11|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nSM was also one of fifteen companies sued and fined by the KFTC for [[Fair Trade Commission (South Korea)#2011 music price fixing scandal.5B1.5D|price rigging in 2011]].\n\nIn 2012, SM was accused of colluding with music distributors, but was cleared of the charge. On August 16, the Seoul High Court revealed their verdict on the issue: \"The KFTC has canceled all corrective orders against SM Entertainment, and the lawsuit costs will be paid by the defendant.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.hankooki.com/lpage/music/201208/sp2012081614244995510.htm|title=SM\uc5d4\ud130'\uc74c\uc6d0\uc720\ud1b5 \ub2f4\ud569' \uc624\uba85 \ubc97\uc5b4|date=16 August 2012|newspaper=Sports Hankooki|language=Korean|trans-title=SM Entertainment cleared of accusations of colluding with music distributors|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Red Velvet music video controversy===\nIn August 2014, after the release of [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]'s music video for \"[[Happiness (Red Velvet song)|Happiness]]\", Japanese media reported that images referencing the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]], as well as the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]], were seen in the background of the video. SM Entertainment responded to the reports, stating that \"after questioning the director, we found that he simply used a collage source for the images, and there was no intention behind it.\" The representative added, \"As SM wasn't able to catch it before, we will remove the material that caused the misunderstanding as soon as possible. We will make sure not to let this kind of thing happen in the future.\" SM later uploaded a new version of the music video without the controversial images.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnetamerica.com/news/article/72424/redvelvet-releases-mv-again|title=[Video] Red Velvet Re-Releases 'Happiness' MV with Edited Scenes|website=www.mnetamerica.com|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Pop music|South Korea}}\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.smtown.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to SM Entertainment\n|list=\n{{SM Entertainment}}\n{{SM Town}}\n{{K-pop}}\n{{KRX 100 companies}}\n{{Film distributors of South Korea}}\n{{Television production companies of South Korea}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:SM Entertainment]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Seoul]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on KOSDAQ]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music record labels]]\n[[Category:Event management companies of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Music production companies]]\n[[Category:Music publishing companies of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Soul music record labels]]\n[[Category:South Korean brands]]\n[[Category:South Korean record labels]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of South Korea]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:587:465a:1f00:18dc:c55a:473c:f402", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u03a4\u03b5\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd\u03b3\u03ba)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SM_Entertainment"}
{"title_page": "Rog\u00e9rio Ceni", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian football manager and former player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Portuguese name|M\u00fccke|Ceni}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Rog\u00e9rio Ceni\n| image = Rog\u00e9rio Ceni.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Rog\u00e9rio Ceni in 2005\n| fullname = Rog\u00e9rio M\u00fccke Ceni\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|1|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"ceni\">{{cite web|title =Rogerio Ceni Profile |url=http://www.m.goal.com/en-gb/people/brazil/9286/rog%C3%A9rio-cenibcsdhfskj |publisher=Goal.Com}}{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Pato Branco]], Brazil\n| height = 1.88 m\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[Fortaleza Esporte Clube|Fortaleza]] (coach)\n| youthyears1 = 1987\u20131989\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sinop Futebol Clube|Sinop]]\n| youthyears2 = 1990\u20131993\n| youthclubs2 = [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC|S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n| clubs1 = [[Sinop Futebol Clube|Sinop]]\n| caps1 = 0\n| goals1 = 0\n| years1 = 1990\n| years2 = 1992\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC|S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n| caps2 = 575\n| goals2 = 65\n| totalcaps = 575\n| totalgoals = 65\n| nationalyears1 = 1997\u20132006\n| nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 16\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2017\n| managerclubs1 = [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC|S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n| manageryears2 = 2017\u20132019\n| managerclubs2 = [[Fortaleza Esporte Clube|Fortaleza]]\n| manageryears3 = 2019\n| managerclubs3 = [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]]\n| manageryears4 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs4 = [[Fortaleza Esporte Clube|Fortaleza]]\n| pcupdate =\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 Japan\u2013South Korea]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup|1997 Saudi Arabia]]|}}\n}}\n'''Rog\u00e9rio M\u00fccke Ceni''' ({{IPA-pt|\u0281o\u02c8\u0292\u025b\u027eiu \u02c8s\u1ebdni|br}}; born 22 January 1973) is a Brazilian [[Association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]] and former player who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. He currently manages [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]] side [[Fortaleza Esporte Clube|Fortaleza]].\n\nMost of his vast professional career, which had spanned 25 years and [[List of footballers with the most official appearances|1,257 professional club matches]], was associated with S\u00e3o Paulo, with which he won 20 major titles, including three [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|Brazilian Leagues]], two [[Copa Libertadores]] and the [[2005 FIFA Club World Championship|2005]] [[FIFA Club World Cup]]. He also scored 131 goals during his career, with most of them coming from [[Direct free kick|free kicks]] and [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalties]] and one coming from open play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2011/mar/28/rogerio-ceni-100-goals-and-counting|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni: 100 goals and counting|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 March 2011|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1551015.html|title=Kings of the free-kick|publisher=FIFA|date=2 December 2011|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> \nHe is recognised by the [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]] as the [[List of goalscoring goalkeepers|goalkeeper to have scored the most goals]] in the history of football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/2292/editorials/2011/03/28/2415054/rogerio-ceni-top-10-goalscoring-goalkeepers|title=Rogerio Ceni & Top 10 goalscoring goalkeepers|publisher=Goal.com|date=28 March 2011|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iffhs.de/?b4a390f03be4ac07cda15b45fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aee0a|title=World Record of the national championships (1888/89-2008)|publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]]|date=20 October 2008|accessdate=7 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nCeni also represented [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] 16 times over the course of his career, being part of the squads that won the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] and the [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and also taking part at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. Ceni is considered one of the all-time greatest Brazilian goalkeepers.<ref name=\"Brazil's 10 Best Goalkeepers\">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1478781-ranking-brazils-10-best-goalkeepers-of-all-time |title=Ranking Brazil's 10 Best Goalkeepers of All Time |publisher=Bleacher Report |author1=Christopher Atkins |date=10 January 2013 |accessdate=21 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n{{expand section|date=January 2020}}\n\nRog\u00e9rio M\u00fccke Ceni was born 22 January 1973<ref name=\"ceni\" /> in [[Pato Branco]], [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n==Club career==\n[[File:SPFC squad - 2005 - 01.jpg|thumb|right|Rog\u00e9rio Ceni with [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC]] in 2005.]]{{Prose|section|date=January 2020}}\nCeni made his senior debuts with [[Sinop Futebol Clube]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/mt/noticia/2014/11/campeao-estadual-pelo-sinop-rogerio-ceni-volta-mt-apos-14-anos.html|title=Campe\u00e3o estadual pelo Sinop, Rog\u00e9rio Ceni volta a MT ap\u00f3s 14 anos|work=Globo Esporte|date=22 November 2014|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> In 1990, the 17-year-old joined [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC]], spending his first six seasons in [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|S\u00e9rie A]] as a backup or third-choice.\n\nOn 25 June 1993 Ceni made his first team debut, starting in a 4\u20131 win against [[CD Tenerife]] for the Trofeo Ciudad de Santiago de Compostela [[Exhibition match|friendly]] championship. In the following year he was utilized as a starter in [[1994 Copa CONMEBOL|the year]]'s [[Copa CONMEBOL]], appearing in all matches as his side was crowned champions.\n\nIn the [[1997 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|1997 season]], after legendary [[Zetti]] moved to [[Santos FC]], Ceni was chosen as his replacement. On 14 July 2005, Ceni was S\u00e3o Paulo's [[Captain (association football)|captain]] as the team [[2005 Copa Libertadores|won the 2005]] [[Copa Libertadores]], a third for the club. Two weeks later, in a match against [[Clube Atl\u00e9tico Mineiro]], he broke the record for most appearances for the team, with 618 matches&nbsp;\u2013 he wore a special commemorative jersey that had the number \"618\" printed on the back; on 25 July of the following year, he scored a penalty against Mexican side [[C.D. Guadalajara]] (also a match-winner), becoming the ''Tricolor'''s all-time leading scorer in the Libertadores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/articulos_ver.jsp?id=59327&slangab=E|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090622122548/http://www.conmebol.com/articulos_ver.jsp?id=59327&slangab=E|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 June 2009|title=Great victory of S\u00e3o Paulo FC against Chivas in Mexico|publisher=CONMEBOL.com|accessdate=5 December 2007|work=CONMEBOL.com}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005\u201307, he scored an astonishing 47 goals in all competitions combined, as the club won two national championships and the [[2005 FIFA Club World Championship|2005]] [[FIFA Club World Cup]]; in the latter competition, he netted in the semifinals against [[Ittihad FC]] (3\u20132, through a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]), and was voted ''[[Man of the match]]'' in [[2005 FIFA Club World Championship Final|the final]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], as well as the tournament's [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512338.html|title=FIFA Club World Championship Japan 2005|publisher=FIFA|date=|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2006, Ceni scored his 63rd and record-breaking goal by netting a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] against [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube]] in the domestic league, a few minutes after denying a penalty to the opposition. Later in the same match, he scored a goal from the spot and took his total to 64, also tying the match 2\u20132; this put him two goals ahead of the previous holder, [[Paraguay]]an [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Chilavert]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=105343.html|title=Rogerio Ceni, the record breaker|publisher=FIFA|date=22 August 2006|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 October 2006, Ceni made his 700th official appearance for S\u00e3o Paulo, against [[Figueirense Futebol Clube]] in a 2\u20130 victory. Some of the gloss was taken off the occasion when the player was ordered to change his bright yellow jersey because it clashed with the [[Referee (association football)|referee]]'s; at the end of the [[2007 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|2007 season]], which ended in league conquest, he was voted by the [[Brazilian Football Confederation]] as the Best Player.\n\nIn April 2009, Ceni fractured his [[ankle]] in training, being initially sidelined for six months,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/Esportes/Noticias/Times/Sao_Paulo/0,,MUL1083408-9875,00-CENI+FRATURA+TORNOZELO+VAI+SER+OPERADO+E+ESTA+FORA+DO+PAULISTA+E+DA+LIBERTA.html|title=Ceni fratura tornozelo, vai ser operado e est\u00e1 fora do Paulista e da Libertadores|trans-title=Ceni fractures ankle, will undergo surgery and is out of ''Paulista'' and ''Libertadores''|work=Globo Esporte|language=Portuguese|date=13 April 2009|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref> but recovering sooner than expected. On 28 October 2010, against [[Clube Atl\u00e9tico Paranaense]], he played his 700th game as club captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lancenet.com.br/minuto/Super-capitao-Rogerio-Ceni-Paulo_0_361164096.html|title=Supercapit\u00e3o: 700 vezes Rog\u00e9rio Ceni no S\u00e3o Paulo|trans-title=Supercaptain: 700 times Rog\u00e9rio Ceni at S\u00e3o Paulo|publisher=Lance Net|language=Portuguese|date=28 October 2010|accessdate=1 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008010300/http://www.lancenet.com.br/minuto/Super-capitao-Rogerio-Ceni-Paulo_0_361164096.html|archivedate=8 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following year, on 27 March, he scored from a free kick to win it against arch rivals [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista]], shooting from 18 metres for his 100th goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/feedarticle/9567299|title=Goalkeeper Rogerio scores 100th goal in S\u00e3o Paulo win|work=The Guardian|location=UK|date=28 March 2011|accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 September 2011, Ceni made his 1000th appearance for S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/sports/2011-09/08/c_131114798.htm|title=Sao Paulo wins in Rogerio Ceni's 1000th game|agency=Xinhuanet|location=China|date=8 September 2011|accessdate=8 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108142829/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/sports/2011-09/08/c_131114798.htm|archivedate=8 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In late January of the following year, the 39-year-old underwent an operation on his [[shoulder]], losing six months of competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/esporte/1039818-sao-paulo-anuncia-que-rogerio-ceni-fara-cirurgia-no-ombro.shtml|title=S\u00e3o Paulo anuncia que Rog\u00e9rio Ceni far\u00e1 cirurgia no ombro|trans-title=S\u00e3o Paulo announces Rog\u00e9rio Ceni will have shoulder surgery|publisher=Folha.com|language=Portuguese|date=26 January 2012|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 2012, Ceni returned to the field, scoring from a direct free kick in a 2\u20130 [[Copa Sudamericana]] away win against [[Esporte Clube Bahia]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/jogo/copa-sul-americana-2012/01-08-2012/bahia-sao-paulo.html|title=Ceni e Ademilson marcam, S\u00e3o Paulo bate Bahia e fica perto da vaga|trans-title=Ceni and Ademilson score, S\u00e3o Paulo defeats Bahia and gets closer to the qualification|work=Globo Esporte|language=pt|date=1 August 2012|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> his side went on to win [[2012 Copa Sudamericana|that year]]'s tournament. He subsequently scored three goals in the league, ending the campaign as a starter.\n\nDespite already aged 40, Ceni stated that his spirit for competition was the same as an eighteen-year-old's, but still stating that his recovery is harder than years ago.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/sao-paulo/noticia/2013/01/aos-40-senhor-ceni-avisa-espirito-de-competicao-ainda-tem-18.html|title=Aos 40, senhor Ceni avisa: 'Esp\u00edrito de competi\u00e7\u00e3o ainda tem 18'|trans-title=40, Mr. Ceni warns: 'Competition spirit still has 18'|work=Globo Esporte|language=pt|date=21 January 2013|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> On 14 July 2013, Ceni scored his 111th goal from a free kick in a 2\u20133 loss at [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria]].\n\nOn 7 December 2013, after lengthy negotiations, Ceni renewed his contract with ''Tricolor'' for a further season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lancenet.com.br/sao-paulo/Rogerio-Ceni-aposentadoria-renova-Paulo_0_1042695934.html|title=Mito fica! Rog\u00e9rio Ceni renova com o S\u00e3o Paulo por uma temporada|trans-title=''Mito'' stays! Rog\u00e9rio Ceni renews with S\u00e3o Paulo for one season|publisher=[[Lance!]]|language=pt|date=7 December 2013|accessdate=28 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220032045/http://www.lancenet.com.br/sao-paulo/Rogerio-Ceni-aposentadoria-renova-Paulo_0_1042695934.html|archivedate=20 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 20 April 2014, in a 3\u20130 home win against [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]], he had three records recognized by [[Guinness World Records]]: most goals scored by a goalkeeper, number of games played for the same club and number of times as captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saopaulofc.net/noticias/noticias/futebol/2014/4/20/rogerio-consequencia-do-trabalho/|title=Rog\u00e9rio: \"Consequ\u00eancia do trabalho\"|trans-title=Rog\u00e9rio: \"Consequence of work\"|publisher=S\u00e3o Paulo's official website|language=pt|date=20 April 2014|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 2014, Ceni broke [[Ryan Giggs]]' record for most wins at a single club after playing in S\u00e3o Paulo's 3\u20130 win over [[Goi\u00e1s Esporte Clube|Goi\u00e1s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/sao-paulo/story/2113922/rogerio-ceni-breaks-ryan-giggs-record-for-most-wins-at-a-single-club/|title=Rogerio Ceni broke Ryan Giggs' record for most wins at a single club|publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|date=28 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322041639/http://www.espnfc.com/sao-paulo/story/2113922/rogerio-ceni-breaks-ryan-giggs-record-for-most-wins-at-a-single-club|archivedate=22 March 2015|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/brazil-goalkeeper-rogerio-ceni-breaks-ryan-giggs-record-for-most-wins-with-one-club-102914|title=Brazil goalkeeper breaks Ryan Giggs' record for most wins with one club|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|date=29 October 2014|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> He finished [[2014 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|the campaign]] with eight league goals (his best goal scoring record within seven years), being an undisputed starter.\n\nOn 28 November 2014, Ceni signed a new deal with S\u00e3o Paulo, until August 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esportes.estadao.com.br/noticias/futebol,sao-paulo-renova-com-rogerio-ceni-ate-agosto-do-ano-que-vem,1599439|title=S\u00e3o Paulo renova com Rog\u00e9rio Ceni at\u00e9 agosto do ano que vem|trans-title=S\u00e3o Paulo renews with Rog\u00e9rio Ceni until August of the following year|publisher=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]|language=pt|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> despite previously stating that he would retire at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esportes.terra.com.br/sao-paulo/videos/rogerio-ceni-confirma-aposentadoria-ao-final-de-2014,7392882.html|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni confirma aposentadoria ao final de 2014|trans-title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni confirms retirement at the end of 2014|publisher=Terra|language=pt|date=4 April 2014|accessdate=28 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111112050/http://esportes.terra.com.br/sao-paulo/videos/rogerio-ceni-confirma-aposentadoria-ao-final-de-2014,7392882.html|archivedate=11 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 29 March 2015, after scoring in a 3\u20130 home win against [[Clube Atl\u00e9tico Linense|Linense]], he surpassed [[Marcelinho Carioca]] in the number of goals scored by direct free kicks for only one club, with Ceni having 60 and Marcelinho, 59.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futebolemnumeros.blogosfera.uol.com.br/2015/03/29/ceni-supera-marcelinho-em-gols-de-falta-por-um-so-clube/|title=Ceni supera Marcelinho em gols de falta por um s\u00f3 clube|trans-title=Ceni overcomes Marcelinho in free kick goals for one club only|publisher=Futebol em N\u00fameros|language=pt|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Ceni scored his 128th goal, entering in the club's top 10 goalscorers list.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3110725/Sao-Paulo-goalkeeper-Rogerio-Ceni-enters-club-s-10-time-goalscorers-list-late-winner-against-Santos.html | title=S\u00e3o Paulo goalkeeper Rogerio Ceni enters club's top 10 all-time goalscorers list | publisher=Dailymail | date=4 June 2015 | accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> Ceni announced his retirement from professional football on 6 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bleacherreport.com/articles/2596345-rogerio-ceni-announces-retirement-after-1256-games-and-131-goals | title=Rogerio Ceni retires after 1,256 games and 131 goals | publisher=Bleacher Report | date=6 December 2015 | accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nA [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian international]] for nine years, Ceni collected 16 [[Cap (sport)|caps]]. He was selected to the squads that won the [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] (and the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], still not fully recovered from [[knee]] surgery<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parana-online.com.br/editoria/especiais/news/157945/?noticia=ROGERIO+CENI+OPERA+JOELHO+E+DESFALCA+SAO+PAULO+POR+UM+MES|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni opera joelho e desfalca S\u00e3o Paulo por um m\u00eas|trans-title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni has knee operation, out for one month|publisher=Paran\u00e1 Online|language=Portuguese|date=11 January 2006|accessdate=1 February 2012}}</ref>), but only appeared in two games in final stages, the 3\u20132 win against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the first tournament and the 4\u20131 triumph over [[Japan national football team|Japan]] in the third.<ref>{{FIFA player|178788}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nIn December 2016, Ceni was appointed as S\u00e3o Paulo coach, with Englishman Michael Beale and Frenchman Charles Hembert joining as his assistants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni talks about his new assistants at S\u00e3o Paulo: \"I'm bringing new things\"|url=http://www.sambafoot.com/en/news/85402_rogerio_ceni_talks_about_his_new_assistants_at_sao_paulo___i_m_bringing_new_things_.html|publisher=Sambafoot}}</ref> In 3 July 2017, after poor results - S\u00e3o Paulo were eliminated in [[2017 Campeonato Paulista|State League]], [[2017 Copa do Brasil|Brazilian Cup]] and [[2017 Copa Sudamericana]] into a period of one month<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/esporte/2017/05/1883329-sao-paulo-empata-sofre-terceira-eliminacao-consecutiva-e-e-vaiado.shtml|title=S\u00e3o Paulo empata, sofre terceira elimina\u00e7\u00e3o consecutiva e \u00e9 vaiado|publisher=}}</ref> and are in relegation zone in [[2017 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|Brazilian League]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esportes.estadao.com.br/noticias/futebol,sao-paulo-perde-do-flamengo-e-entra-na-zona-de-rebaixamento-do-brasileirao,70001874193|title=S\u00e3o Paulo perde do Flamengo e entra na zona de rebaixamento do Brasileir\u00e3o - Esportes - Estad\u00e3o|publisher=}}</ref> he was sacked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/sao-paulo/noticia/sao-paulo-demite-rogerio-ceni.ghtml|title=S\u00e3o Paulo demite Rog\u00e9rio Ceni|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.uol.com.br/noticia/707908_seis-meses-depois-rogerio-ceni-deixa-o-sao-paulo|title=Seis meses depois, Rog\u00e9rio Ceni deixa o S\u00e3o Paulo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/sao-paulo/story/3152645/sao-paulo-sack-coach-rogerio-ceni-after-six-months-in-charge|title=Sao Paulo sack coach Rogerio Ceni after six months in charge|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCeni signed with [[Fortaleza Esporte Clube|Fortaleza]] to coach the team in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lozetti|first1=Alexandre|last2=Tha\u00eds|first2=Jorge|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni assina com o Fortaleza e \u00e9 novo t\u00e9cnico para 2018|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/ce/futebol/noticia/rogerio-ceni-assina-com-o-fortaleza-e-e-novo-tecnico-para-2018.ghtml|website=globoesporte.com|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> On 3 November of that year, Fortaleza clinched promotion to the [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|S\u00e9rie A]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Dirigido por Ceni, Fortaleza vence e garante acesso \u00e0 S\u00e9rie A de 2019|url=https://esportes.estadao.com.br/noticias/futebol,dirigido-por-ceni-fortaleza-vence-e-garante-acesso-a-serie-a-de-2019,70002583761|website=https://www.estadao.com.br/|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> and seven days later, the club clinched the [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B|S\u00e9rie B]] title for the first time in its history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fortaleza vence o Ava\u00ed fora de casa e conquista o t\u00edtulo in\u00e9dito da S\u00e9rie B|url=https://www.opovo.com.br/esportes/futebol/times/fortaleza/2018/11/fortaleza-vence-o-avai-fora-de-casa-e-conquista-o-titulo-inedito-da-se.html|website=https://www.opovo.com.br/|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Fortaleza also won the [[Campeonato Cearense]] and the [[Copa do Nordeste]].\n\nOn 11 August 2019, Ceni was named [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]] manager,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/cruzeiro/noticia/cruzeiro-anuncia-a-contratacao-de-rogerio-ceni.ghtml|website=globoesporte.com|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> but was dismissed on 26 September, after having altercations with the club's main players, specifically [[Thiago Neves]] and [[Ded\u00e9 (footballer, born 1988)|Ded\u00e9]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazetaesportiva.com/times/cruzeiro/rogerio-ceni-deixa-o-comando-do-cruzeiro/|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni deixa o comando do Cruzeiro|date=2019-09-26|website=Gazeta Esportiva|language=pt-BR|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> Three days later, he was announced at his former side Fortaleza, replacing fired [[Z\u00e9 Ricardo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/ce/futebol/noticia/fortaleza-anuncia-retorno-de-rogerio-ceni.ghtml|title=Fortaleza anuncia retorno de Rog\u00e9rio Ceni|trans-title=Fortaleza announce the return of Rog\u00e9rio Ceni|publisher=Globo Esporte|language=pt-BR|date=29 September 2019|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA dead-ball specialist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/33006305|title=Rogerio Ceni: Sao Paulo keeper into club record books|publisher=BBC|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Ceni was the official taker of free kicks and penalties for S\u00e3o Paulo from 1997 until his retirement, a time period in which he scored 131 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futdados.com/raio-x-de-todos-os-gols-de-rogerio-ceni/|title=Raio-X de todos os gols de Rog\u00e9rio Ceni|trans-title=X-Ray of all Rog\u00e9rio Ceni goals|publisher=Futdados|language=pt|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> In addition to his accurate set-pieces, prolific goalscoring, distribution, and ability with the ball at his feet,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/en/12102015-1545/farewell-rogerio-ceni-gunner-gloves|title=The farewell of Rogerio Ceni, the gunner with gloves|publisher=CONMEBOL|date=10 December 2015|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2011/mar/28/rogerio-ceni-100-goals-and-counting|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni: 100 goals and counting|work=The Guardian|author1=Barney Ronay|date=28 March 2011|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> he was also known as an excellent goalkeeper and shot-stopper,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/rogerio-ceni-most-prolific-goalscoring-200428305.html|title=Rogerio Ceni: The most prolific goalscoring keeper ever|publisher=Yahoo|author1=Prayank Sam|date=5 October 2015|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> and stood out for his determination and longevity throughout his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/y=2010/m=4/news=ceni-still-set-his-ways-1201590.html|title=Ceni still set in his ways|publisher=FIFA|date=28 April 2010|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Ceni was known for being capable of producing brilliant saves, such as those in the final of the 2005 FIFA Club World Championship, which saw S\u00e3o Paulo defeat Liverpool 1\u20130; for his performances, Ceni later won the [[2005 FIFA Club World Championship#Awards|Golden Ball]], which is awarded to the competition's best player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saopaulofc.net/noticias/noticias/historia/2011/12/17/rogerio-ceni-coloca-o-japao-aos-seus-pes/|title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni coloca o Jap\u00e3o aos seus p\u00e9s|trans-title=Rog\u00e9rio Ceni puts Japan at his feet|publisher=S\u00e3o Paulo's official website|language=pt|date=17 December 2011|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> He is considered to be one of Brazil's greatest goalkeepers ever.<ref name=\"Brazil's 10 Best Goalkeepers\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{importance section|date=January 2020}}\nCeni is different from several footballers: he prefers [[Rock music|rock]] instead of [[Pagode (music)|pagode]], a Brazilian musical style, common among football players, and has a more classical style of dressing. According to Ceni: \"I like to dress in a good way. I like to kick free kicks. I do not do to make myself. I feel well.\"<ref>RIBEIRO, Arnaldo. \"Ponte que partiu! \u00c9 o melhor goleiro do Brasil\". S\u00e3o Paulo, Abril, Placar Magazine, Dec. 2000, p. 50-55</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|6 December 2015}}<ref>{{Soccerway|rogerio-ceni/9373|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>https://www.footballdatabase.eu/fr/joueur/details/14385--rogerio_ceni</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align: center; width=70%\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=10%|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=7% |[[Season]]\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|[[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|S\u00e9rie A]]\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|[[Copa do Brasil]]\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|[[CONMEBOL|Continental<br>Competitions]]<sup>'''[[#1|1]]'''</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|Other<br>Tournaments<sup>'''[[#2|2]]'''</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|Total\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|Friendlies\n!colspan=\"2\" width=10%|Overall Total\n|- \t \n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n|- align=center\n|'''[[Sinop Futebol Clube|Sinop]]'''\n|[[1990 in Brazilian football|1990]] ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| 20 || 0 \n! 20\n! 0\n|colspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n! 20\n! 0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"25\" align=center|'''[[S\u00e3o Paulo FC|S\u00e3o Paulo]]'''\n|- align=center\n|[[1993 S\u00e3o Paulo FC season|19