ttp://www.byzantinecatholic.org/our-heritage/history-of-our-lady-of-fatima/}}<ref>\n|-\n|St. Agnes\n|\n|1025 Masonic Ave\n|Parish dates to 1893; addition to church in 1953<ref>{{cite web|title=History of St. Agnes Parish|publisher=St. Agnes Catholic Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.saintagnessf.org/history.html}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Dominic Church in San Francisco|St. Dominic]]\n|[[File:Exterior view of St- Dominic catholic church 2013-10-19 14-56.jpg|100px]]\n|2390 Bush St\n|Parish established 1873; Gothic style church completed 1928; flying buttresses added in early 1990s for seismic stability<ref>{{cite web|title=Parish History|publisher=St. Dominic Catholic Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://stdominics.org/parish}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Benedict Parish for the Deaf\n|\n|1801 Octavia St\n|Established in 1984 as the only deaf Catholic parish in the Western United States<ref>{{cite web|title=History|publisher=St. Benedict Parish for the Deaf|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://sfdeafcatholics.org/about-us/history/}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Ignatius Church in San Francisco|St. Ignatius]]\n|[[File:Saint Ignatius Church (San Francisco).jpg|100px]]\n|650 Parker Ave\n|Parish formed 1855; current Italian Renaissance and Baroque church dedicated in 1914<ref>{{cite web|title=History|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.stignatiussf.org/overview/history}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Monica\n|\n|470 24th Ave\n|Parish dates to 1911; current church dedicated in 1918<ref>{{cite web|title=History of St. Monica Parish|publisher=Saint Monica-Saint Thomas the Apostle Parish|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://smstaparishsf.org/about/history/}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Thomas the Apostle\n|\n|3835 Balboa St\n|First church built 1923, expanded 1930<ref>{{cite web|title=History of St. Thomas the ApostleParish|publisher=Saint Monica-Saint Thomas the Apostle Parish|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://smstaparishsf.org/about/history/}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Vincent de Paul Church in San Francisco|St. Vincent de Paul]]\n|[[File:St. Vincent de Paul Church, San Francisco.jpg|100px]]\n|2320 Green St\n|Parish in Pacific Heights neighborhood formed in 1901; new church opened in 1913 became known as the \"Church of the Exposition\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The History of St. Vincent de Paul Church - San Francisco|publisher=St. Vincent de Paul Parish in San Francisco|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://www.svdpsf.org/history.html}}</ref>\n|-\n|Star of the Sea\n|\n|4420 Geary Blvd\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=Star of the Sea Catholic Church|accessdate=Apri 20, 2020|url=https://starparish.com/}}</ref>\n|-\n|Nativity of Our Lord\n|\n|240 Fell St\n|Dedicated in 1904, began as a parish serving the Croation and Slovenian immigrants<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|publisher=Nativity of Our Lord Roman Catholic Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://www.sfnativity.org/aboutus.html}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Deanery 4===\nDeanery 4 consists of San Francisco's Financial District, [[Chinatown]], [[North Beach, San Francisco, California|North Beach]], [[Tenderloin, San Francisco|Tenderloin District]], and [[South of Market, San Francisco, California|SOMA]] areas.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''\n|-\n|[[Notre-Dame-des-Victoires, San Francisco|Notre Dame des Victoires]]\n|[[File:NDdesVictoiresSF.jpg|100px]]\n|566 Bush St\n|Designated as a San Francisco Historic landmark\n|-\n|[[Old Saint Mary's Cathedral|Old St. Mary's Cathedral]]\n|[[File:OldSaintMarysCathedralSF.jpg|100px]]\n|660 California St\n|Gothic Revival church built in 1854, designated a San Francisco landmark\n|-\n|St. Boniface\n|\n|133 Golden Gate Ave\n|\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's Catholic Church (San Francisco, California)|St.  Patrick]]\n|[[File:St Patrick Catholic Church, San Francisco.jpg|100px]]\n|756 Mission St\n|Church rebuilt after San Francisco Earthquake, designated as a San Francisco landmark\n|-\n|[[Sts. Peter and Paul Church, San Francisco|Sts. Peter and Paul]]\n|[[File:Saints Peter and Paul Church.JPG|100px]]\n|666 Filbert St\n|Once known as the Italian Cathedral of the West, completed in 1924\n|-\n|National Shrine of St. Francis of Assisi\n|\n|610 Vallejo St\n|\n|}\n\n===Deanery 5===\nDeanery 5 consists of the [[Mission District]], [[Bernal Heights]], [[Glen Park, San Francisco|Glen Park]], [[Potrero Hill]], and [[Noe Valley]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''\n|-\n|Mission Dolores Basilica and [[Mission San Francisco de Asis]]\n|\n|3321 16th St\n|The mission building is the oldest surviving structure in San Francisco; the basilica was added in 1918\n|-\n|Immaculate Conception Chapel\n|\n|3255 Folsom St\n|Part of St. Anthony of Padua parish\n|-\n|St. Anthony of Padua\n|\n|3215 Cesar Chavez\n|\n|-\n|St. Charles Borromeo\n|\n|701 S Van Ness Ave\n|\n|-\n|St. James\n|\n|1086 Guerrero St\n|\n|-\n|St. John the Evangelist\n|\n|19 St Marys Ave\n|\n|-\n|St. Kevin\n|\n|704 Cortland Ave\n|\n|-\n|[[St. Paul's Catholic Church (San Francisco)|St. Paul]]\n|[[File:St. Paul's Catholic Church (San Francisco).jpg|100px]]\n|221 Valley St\n|Parish church in [[Noe Valley]] neighborhood, completed in 1911\n|-\n|St. Peter\n|\n|1200 Florida St\n|\n|-\n|St. Philip the Apostle\n|\n|725 Diamond St\n|\n|-\n|St. Teresa of Avila\n|\n|1490 19th St\n|\n|}\n\n==Marin County==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''\n|-\n|Our Lady of Loretto\n|\n|1806 Novato Boulevard, Novato\n|\n|-\n|Our Lady of Mount Carmel\n|\n|3 Oakdale Avenue, Mill Valley\n|\n|-\n|Sacred Heart\n|\n|10189 State Route, #1, Olema\n|\n|-\n|St. Anselm\n|\n|97 Shady Lane and Bolinas, San Anselmo\n|\n|-\n|St. Anthony of Padua\n|\n|1000 Cambridge Street, Novato\n|\n|-\n|St. Cecilia\n|\n|450 Cintura Ave, Lagunitas, CA\n|\n|-\n|St. Hillary\n|\n|761 Hilary Drive, Tiburon\n|\n|-\n|St. Isabella\n|\n|San Rafael, CA\n|\n|-\n|St. Mary Star of the Sea\n|\n|180 Harrison Avenue, Sausalito\n|\n|-\n|St. Patrick\n|\n|114 King Street, Larkspur\n|\n|-\n|St. Raphael\n|\n|1104 Fifth Avenue, San Rafael\n|\n|-\n|St. Rita\n|\n|100 Marinda Drive, Fairfax\n|\n|-\n|St. Sebastian\n|\n|373 Bon Air Road, Kentfield\n|\n|}\n\n==San Mateo County==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''\n|-\n|All Souls\n|\n|315 Walnut Avenue, South San Francisco\n|\n|-\n|Church of the Good Shepherd\n|\n|901 Oceana Boulevard, Pacifica\n|\n|-\n|Church of the Nativity\n|\n|210 Oak Grove Avenue, Menlo Park\n|\n|-\n|Holy Angels\n|\n|107 San Pedro Road, Colma\n|\n|-\n|Immaculate Heart of Mary\n|\n|1040 Alameda De Las Pulgas, Belmont\n|\n|-\n|Mater Dolorosa\n|\n|307 Willow Avenue, South San Francisco\n|\n|-\n|Our Lady of Angels\n|\n|1721 Hillside Drive, Burlingame\n|\n|-\n|Our Lady of Mercy\n|\n|1 Elmwood Drive, Daly City\n|\n|-\n|Our Lady of Mount Carmel\n|\n|300 Fulton Street, Redwood City\n|\n|-\n|Our Lady of Perpetual Help\n|\n|60 Wellington Avenue, Daly City\n|\n|-\n|Our Lady of the Pillar\n|\n|400 Church Street, Half Moon Bay\n|\n|-\n|[[Our Lady of the Wayside Church|Our Lady of the Wayside]]\n|[[File:OurLadyoftheWayside.jpg|100px]]\n|930 Portola Road, Portola Valley\n|Mission Revival church built 1912\n|-\n|St. Andrew\n|\n|1571 Southgate Avenue, Daly City\n|\n|-\n|St. Anselm\n|\n|3700 Callan Blvd., South San Francisco\n|\n|-\n|St. Anthony\n|\n|3500 Middlefield Road, Menlo Park\n|\n|-\n|St. Bartholomew\n|\n|300 Alameda De Las Pulgas, San Mateo\n|\n|-\n|St. Bruno\n|\n|555 W. San Bruno Avenue, San Bruno\n|\n|-\n|St. Catherine of Siena\n|\n|1310 Bayswater Avenue, Burlingame\n|\n|-\n|St. Charles\n|\n|880 Tamarack Avenue, San Carlos\n|\n|-\n|St. Denis\n|\n|2250 Avy Avenue, Menlo Park\n|\n|-\n|St. Dunstan\n|\n|1133 Broadway, Millbrae\n|\n|-\n|St. Francis of Assisi\n|\n|1425 Bay Road, East Palo Alto\n|\n|-\n|St. Gregory\n|\n|2715 Hacienda Street, San Mateo\n|\n|-\n|St. Luke\n|\n|1111 Beach Park, Foster City\n|\n|-\n|St. Mark\n|\n|325 Marine View Avenue, Belmont\n|\n|-\n|St. Matthew\n|\n|1 Notre Dame Avenue, San Mateo\n|\n|-\n|St. Matthias\n|\n|1685 Cordilleras Road, Redwood City\n|\n|-\n|St. Peter\n|\n|700 Oddstad Boulevard, Pacifica\n|\n|-\n|St. Pius\n|\n|1100 Woodside Road, Redwood City\n|\n|-\n|St. Raymond\n|\n|1100 Santa Cruz Avenue, Menlo Park\n|\n|-\n|St. Robert\n|\n|1380 Crystal Springs Road, San Bruno\n|\n|-\n|St. Timothy\n|\n|1515 Dolan Avenue, San Mateo\n|\n|-\n|St. Veronica\n|\n|434 Alida Way, South San Francisco\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of churches in the United States by diocese|San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in California]]\n", "name_user": "Cbl62", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeanery 3:fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_churches_in_the_Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_San_Francisco"}
{"title_page": "Ramos v. Louisiana", "text_new": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n  |Litigants=Ramos v. Louisiana\n  |ArgueDate=October 7\n  |ArgueYear=2019\n  |DecideDate=April 20\n  |DecideYear=2020\n  |FullName=Evangelisto Ramos, Petitioner v. Louisiana\n  |Docket=18\u20135924\n  |USVol=590\n  |USPage=___\n  |ParallelCitations=\n  |Prior=\n  |Subsequent=\n  |Holding=The [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] requires that guilty verdicts for criminal trials must be [[unanimous]].\n  |Majority=Gorsuch\n  |JoinMajority=Ginsburg, Breyer, Sotomayor, Kavanaugh (parts I, II\u2013A, III, IV\u2013B\u20131); Ginsburg, Breyer, Sotomayor (parts II\u2013B, IV\u2013B\u20132, V); Ginsburg, Breyer (part IV\u2013A)\n  |Concurrence=Sotomayor (all but part IV\u2013A)\n  |Concurrence2=Kavanaugh (in part)\n  |Concurrence3=Thomas (in judgment)\n  |Dissent=Alito\n  |JoinDissent=Roberts; Kagan (all but part III\u2013D)\n  |LawsApplied=[[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. VI]]\n  |Overturned previous case=''[[Apodaca v. Oregon]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Ramos v. Louisiana''''', 590 U.S. ___ (2020), was a [[List of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]] [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case in which the Court ruled that the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] requires that guilty verdicts for criminal trials must be [[unanimous]], overturning the Court's previous decision from the 1972 case ''[[Apodaca v. Oregon]]''.<ref>https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/19pdf/18-5924_n6io.pdf</ref><ref name=\"cnn decision\">{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/politics/scotus-jury-verdict-criminal-trial/index.html |title = Supreme Court says unanimous jury verdicts required in state criminal trials for serious offenses | first = Ariana | last= de Vogue | date = April 20, 2020 | accessdate=  April 20, 2020 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] defines procedures for prosecution of criminal cases against individuals, which has been [[Incorporation of the Bill of Rights|incorporated against states]] by various Supreme Court decisions under the [[Due Process Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]. The Sixth Amendment assures a [[jury trial]] for a person charged on a criminal offense, but does not specify the process around that trial, leaving it for states to define within their own constitutions.<ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\nWhile federal law required that a federal jury trial require a unanimous vote to convict on a criminal charge, the 1972 Supreme Court case ''[[Apodaca v. Oregon]]'' ruled that states did not have to follow this. All but two states adopted unanimous jury votes to convict. Oregon allowed a jury vote of 10-2 or more for conviction (of which ''Apodaca v. Oregon'' had challenged), while Louisiana, until 2019, had similarly allowed a 10-2 jury vote to convict, but since had passed a new constitutional amendment requiring a unanimous jury vote for all criminal charges placed on January 1, 2019 or later.<ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\nThe present case's petitioner, Evangelisto Ramos, had been convicted of murder in Louisiana on a 10\u20132 vote in 2016, before the passage of the new constitutional amendment. Ramos appealed the conviction on the issue around the non-unanimous jury factor, arguing that the law, established in 1898, allowed for racial discrimination within juries.<ref name=\"nytimes oral\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/07/us/politics/supreme-court-jury-verdicts.html |title = Supreme Court Weighs Ending Non-Unanimous Jury Verdicts in Criminal Cases | first=  Adam | last = Liptak | date = October 7, 2019 | accessdate = April 20, 2020 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref><ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\nOral hearings for the case were held on October 7, 2019.<ref name=\"nytimes oral\"/>\n\n==Decision==\nThe Court issued its decision on April 20, 2020. In a 6-3 decision, the Court reversed the decision against Ramos and ruled that the unanimity of a jury vote for conviction set by the Sixth Amendment must also be an incorporated right against the states, overturning ''Apodaca v. Oregon''. Justice [[Neil Gorsuch]] wrote the majority opinion, joined in parts by Justices [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]], [[Sonia Sotomayor]], [[Stephen Breyer]] and [[Brett Kavanaugh]], while [[Clarence Thomas]] joined in the judgement only. Justice [[Samuel Alito]] wrote the dissent joined by Chief Justice [[John Roberts]] and [[Elena Kagan]].<ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:2020 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:21st century American trials]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Roberts Court]]\n[[Category:United States Sixth Amendment sentencing case law]]\n[[Category:United States Federal Sentencing Guidelines case law]]\n\n\n{{SCOTUS-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n  |Litigants=Ramos v. Louisiana\n  |ArgueDate=October 7\n  |ArgueYear=2019\n  |DecideDate=April 20\n  |DecideYear=2020\n  |FullName=Evangelisto Ramos, Petitioner v. Louisiana\n  |Docket=18\u20135924\n  |USVol=590\n  |USPage=___\n  |ParallelCitations=\n  |Prior=\n  |Subsequent=\n  |Holding=The [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] requires that guilty verdicts for criminal trials must be [[unanimous]].\n  |Majority=Gorsuch\n  |JoinMajority=Ginsburg, Breyer, Sotomayor, Kavanaugh (parts I, II\u2013A, III, IV\u2013B\u20131); Ginsburg, Breyer, Sotomayor (parts II\u2013B, IV\u2013B\u20132, V); Ginsburg, Breyer (part IV\u2013A)\n  |Concurrence=Sotomayor (all but part IV\u2013A)\n  |Concurrence2=Kavanaugh (in part)\n  |Concurrence3=Thomas (in judgment)\n  |Dissent=Alito\n  |JoinDissent=Roberts; Kagan (all but part III\u2013D)\n  |LawsApplied=[[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. VI]]\n  |Overturned previous case=''[[Apodaca v. Oregon]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Ramos v. Louisiana''''', 590 U.S. ___ (2020), was a [[List of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]] [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case in which the Court ruled that the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] requires that guilty verdicts for criminal trials must be [[unanimous]], overturning the Court's previous decision from the 1972 case ''[[Apodaca v. Oregon]]''.<ref>https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/19pdf/18-5924_n6io.pdf</ref><ref name=\"cnn decision\">{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/politics/scotus-jury-verdict-criminal-trial/index.html |title = Supreme Court says unanimous jury verdicts required in state criminal trials for serious offenses | first = Ariana | last= de Vogue | date = April 20, 2020 | accessdate=  April 20, 2020 | work = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] defines procedures for prosecution of criminal cases against individuals, which has been [[Incorporation of the Bill of Rights|incorporated against states]] by various Supreme Court decisions under the [[Due Process Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]. The Sixth Amendment assures a [[jury trial]] for a person charged on a criminal offense, but does not specify the process around that trial, leaving it for states to define within their own constitutions.<ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\nWhile federal law required that a federal jury trial require a unanimous vote to convict on a criminal charge, the 1972 Supreme Court case ''[[Apodaca v. Oregon]]'' ruled that states did not have to follow this. All but two states adopted unanimous jury votes to convict. Oregon allowed a jury vote of 10-2 or more for conviction (of which ''Apodaca v. Oregon'' had challenged), while Louisiana, until 2019, had similarly allowed a 10-2 jury vote to convict, but since had passed a new constitutional amendment requiring a unanimous jury vote for all criminal charges placed on January 1, 2019 or later.<ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\nThe present case's petitioner, Evangelisto Ramos, had been convicted of murder in Louisiana on a 10\u20132 vote in 2016, before the passage of the new constitutional amendment. Ramos appealed the conviction on the issue around the non-unanimous jury factor, arguing that the law, established in the 1898, allowed for racial discrimination within juries.<ref name=\"nytimes oral\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/07/us/politics/supreme-court-jury-verdicts.html |title = Supreme Court Weighs Ending Non-Unanimous Jury Verdicts in Criminal Cases | first=  Adam | last = Liptak | date = October 7, 2019 | accessdate = April 20, 2020 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref><ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\nOral hearings for the case were held on October 7, 2019.<ref name=\"nytimes oral\"/>\n\n==Decision==\nThe Court issued its decision on April 20, 2020. In a 6-3 decision, the Court reversed the decision against Ramos and ruled that the unanimity of a jury vote for conviction set by the Sixth Amendment must also be an incorporated right against the states, overturning ''Apodaca v. Oregon''. Justice [[Neil Gorsuch]] wrote the majority opinion, joined in parts by Justices [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]], [[Sonia Sotomayor]], [[Stephen Breyer]] and [[Brett Kavanaugh]], while [[Clarence Thomas]] joined in the judgement only. Justice [[Samuel Alito]] wrote the dissent joined by Chief Justice [[John Roberts]] and [[Elena Kagan]].<ref name=\"cnn decision\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:2020 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:21st century American trials]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Roberts Court]]\n[[Category:United States Sixth Amendment sentencing case law]]\n[[Category:United States Federal Sentencing Guidelines case law]]\n\n\n{{SCOTUS-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kaldari", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramos_v._Louisiana"}
{"title_page": "Michael Jones (actor)", "text_new": "{{other people|Michael Jones|Michael Jones (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Michael Jones\n| image = Michael_Jones_at_RTX_2015.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Jones at the ''Lazer Team'' panel at [[RTX (event)|RTX]] 2015\n| birth_name = Michael Vincent Jones\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|7|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Woodbridge Township, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor, YouTube personality\n| years_active = 2009\u2013present\n| known_for = {{plainlist|\n* [[Achievement Hunter]]\n* ''Rage Quit''\n* ''Internet Box''\n* ''[[Lazer Team]]''\n* ''[[Lazer Team 2]]\n* ''Off Topic''\n* ''Face Jam''\n}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lindsay Jones (actress)|Lindsay Jones]]|May 9, 2014}}\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Michael Vincent Jones''' (born July 24, 1987) is an American actor, voice actor, podcast host and [[internet personality]] and is credited as the founder of Rooster Teeth and [[Rooster Teeth]]'s gameplay division [[Achievement Hunter]]. He is the creator of the acclaimed front back shirt.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Singal|first1=Jesse|title=They're playing video games. And on YouTube, we're watching.|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/2013/07/27/they-playing-video-games-and-youtube-watching/JO1kEZdIHEZTHtMPlVPvYN/story.html|newspaper=Boston Globe\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731151835/http://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/2013/07/27/they-playing-video-games-and-youtube-watching/JO1kEZdIHEZTHtMPlVPvYN/story.html |archive-date=July 31, 2013}}</ref>  He also co-hosted three-time [[Podcast Awards|Podcast Award]] winner ''Internet Box''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |title=2012 Winners and Nominees |publisher=PodcastAwards.com |date=2012-01-07 |accessdate=2015-09-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Lh9tnIpR |archivedate=2013-12-07 }}</ref>\n\nJones has worked extensively with Rooster Teeth, having also starred in the second and third seasons of ''Immersion'', the comedy murder mystery series ''[[Ten Little Roosters]]'', and voices the character [[List of RWBY characters#Haven Academy|Sun Wukong]] in Rooster Teeth's ''[[RWBY]]'', and Max in ''[[Camp Camp]]''. He starred in Rooster Teeth's science fiction action comedy film ''[[Lazer Team]]'', released in 2016, as well as [[Lazer Team 2|its sequel]] the following year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Finn|first1=Elliott|title=Rooster Teeth's 'Lazer Team' Begins Production|url=http://airlockalpha.com/node/10012/rooster-teeths-lazer-team-begins-production.html|website=AirLockAlpha|publisher=Nexus Media Group Inc|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Klima|first1=Jeff|title=Rooster Teeth Crew About Their New Movie Lazer Team|url=http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/11/rooster-teeth-crow-about-their-new-movie-lazer-team/|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis work outside of Rooster Teeth includes voicing Sting Eucliffe in ''[[Fairy Tail]]'', Dogra in ''[[One Piece]]'', Rapture in ''[[Ninja Slayer#Anime|Ninja Slayer From Animation]]'', and Gen in ''[[World Break: Aria of Curse for a Holy Swordsman]]''.\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:RTX 2014 - AH panel (14404155388) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Michael Jones and [[Gavin Free]] on the [[Achievement Hunter]] panel at [[RTX (event)|RTX]] 2014]]\n\nAfter graduating from high school, Jones worked as an electrician for almost five years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYDfKuRJcq0 |title=Retsutalk Episode 41: Trophy Trapper |date=20 November 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |author=Retsuprae}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://ah.roosterteeth.com/archive/?id=10589 |title=Let's Play \u2013 I am Bread Part 4 |date=31 March 2015 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |author=Rooster Teeth|author-link=Rooster Teeth }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OTUw4wo3V5s |title=Rooster Teeth Animated Adventures \u2013 Michael Punches Poo |publisher=[[YouTube]] |author=Rooster Teeth |date=4 December 2013|author-link=Rooster Teeth }}</ref> Jones first came to attention after his video \"[[Crackdown 2]] \u2013 Orbs = Bullshit\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=egxjuLkhXUw |title=Crackdown 2 \u2013 Orbs = Bullshit |publisher=[[YouTube]] |last=Jones |first=Michael |date=6 July 2010}}</ref> reached the front page of [[reddit]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeadSpaceLover|title=What Playing Crackdown 2 Is Really Like NSFW]|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/gaming/comments/f0wxo/what_playing_crackdown_2_is_really_like_nsfw/|website=Reddit|publisher=Reddit|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://roosterteeth.com/podcast/episode.php?id=212 | title = Rooster Teeth Podcast No. 212 |publisher=Rooster Teeth Productions | date = April 2, 2013 | accessdate = January 26, 2015 }}</ref> He received an email from Rooster Teeth asking him to join and make a new show for Achievement Hunter, which became ''Rage Quit''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://roosterteeth.com/episode/rt-podcast-season-1-rt-podcast-228 | title = Rooster Teeth Podcast No. 228 |publisher=Rooster Teeth Productions | date = July 23, 2013 | accessdate = September 13, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bJTmV0qyz-0&list=PL546793E0D9AB4536&index=189 |title=Rage Quit \u2013 Trials HD |publisher=[[YouTube]] |author=LtMkilla |date=20 January 2011}}</ref> In September 2011, he co-founded the triple award-winning ''Internet Box'' podcast<ref name=PodcastWin>{{cite web|url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |title=2012 Winners and Nominees |publisher=PodcastAwards.com |date=2012-01-07 |accessdate=2013-09-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Lh9tnIpR |archivedate=2013-12-07 }}</ref> hosted by himself, [[Barbara Dunkelman]], [[Ray Narvaez, Jr.]], Andrew Blanchard, Mike Kroon, and Dylan \"Dylon\" Saramago, with [[Lindsay Jones (actress)|Lindsay Jones]] and Kerry Shawcross being added to the cast later on.  He is an occasional guest on the ''Rooster Teeth Podcast'' and is currently the main host of the Achievement Hunter podcast ''Off Topic''.\n\nJones has worked as both an actor and a [[voice artist]] in multiple projects, several of which are produced by Rooster Teeth, including roles as Sun Wukong in Rooster Teeth's animated series ''[[RWBY]]'', fictionalized versions of himself in both ''Rooster Teeth Shorts'' and ''[[Ten Little Roosters]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brouwer|first1=Bree|title=Rooster Teeth Asks Fans To Sleuth Out A Killer In 'Ten Little Roosters'|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2014/11/05/rooster-teeth-ten-little-roosters-murder-mystery/|publisher=Tubefilter|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> Mogar in the animated series ''X-Ray and Vav,'' and Zach in the sci-fi comedy film ''[[Lazer Team]] and Lazer Team 2''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/lazer-team-2-premiere-date-trailer-youtube-red-1202606430/|title='Lazer Team 2' Premiere Date Set on YouTube Red, Extended Trailer Released (Watch)|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2017-11-03|work=Variety|access-date=2018-04-23|language=en-US}}</ref> He has co-starred in the Rooster Teeth series ''Immersion'' since season two. His non-Rooster Teeth credits include  the animated shows ''[[Fairy Tail]]'', as [[List of Fairy Tail characters#Sting Eucliffe|Sting Eucliffe]], and ''[[World Break: Aria of Curse for a Holy Swordsman]]'', as Gen. On October 1, 2016, Jones announced via [[Twitter]] that he will be playing Dogra in ''[[One Piece]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=Michael|title=Michael Jones' Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/AH_Michael/status/782354092358144001|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe creator of the video game ''[[Surgeon Simulator 2013|Surgeon Simulator]]'' named the alien character Gworb after a remark made by Jones in a [[Let's Play (video gaming)|Let's Play]] video in which Jones was conversing with [[Gavin Free]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Partridge|first1=Jon|title=Achievement Hunter: The making of a YouTube legend|url=http://www.redbull.com/en/games/stories/1331666237215/achievement-hunter-interview|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> In addition Gworb has an organ known as the \"Gavichal\", which is a combination of Michael Jones' and Gavin Free's names.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Lazer Team premiere - Lindsay and Michael Jones (27404476666).jpg|thumb|right|Michael and his wife Lindsay Jones]]\nJones was born in [[Woodbridge, New Jersey]] to \"devout Roman Catholic parents.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://roosterteeth.com/episode/rt-sponsor-cut-season-2-rooster-teeth-newly-wed-game |publisher=[[Rooster Teeth]] |title=RT Sponsor Cut: Rooster Teeth Newly Wed Game |access-date=September 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://roosterteeth.com/episode/rt-podcast-season-1-rt-podcast-156 |title=RT Podcast #156 |author=Rooster Teeth |date=March 7, 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2014, Jones married long-time girlfriend and Rooster Teeth voice actor [[Lindsay Tuggey]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kane|first1=Bugeja|title=Michael and Lindsay Jones Panel at Supanova 2014|url=http://www.capsulecomputers.com.au/2014/06/michael-and-lindsay-jones-panel-at-supanova-2014/|publisher=Capsule Computers|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> During Rooster Teeth's 2016 [[Extra Life (fundraiser)|Extra Life]] livestream, the couple announced that they are expecting a child, which was later revealed to be a girl in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=egsQY02ELjo |author=Rooster Teeth |title=Michael Jones is having a baby! Rooster Teeth Extra Life 2016 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=November 13, 2016 |accessdate=November 16, 2016|author-link=Rooster Teeth }}</ref> They announced the birth of their daughter, Iris Elise Jones, born May 24, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=Michael|title=Surprise, OUR DAUGHTER IS HERE!!!|url=https://twitter.com/AH_Michael/status/867608127767752704?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet|website=Twitter|publisher=Michael Jones|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> On August 5, 2018, Jones announced at RTX 2018 that he and Lindsay were expecting their second child in February 2019. Luna Claire Jones was born February 18, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=Michael|title=Mom & Dad x2|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BuC8VDPBE1j/|website=Instagram|publisher=Michael Jones|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2016\n| ''[[Lazer Team]]''\n| Zach<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fox7austin.com/good-day/83303645-story |title=Rooster Teeth's 'Lazer Team' |first=Dave |last=Froehlich |date=29 January 2016 |publisher=[[KTBC (TV)]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/lazer-team |magazine=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=25 January 2016 |first=Clayton |last=Dillard |title=Lazer Team}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/ct-lazer-team-movie-rev-20160129-story.html |title='Lazer Team' review: Goofy blast from the past |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=29 January 2016 |first=Cary |last=Darling}}</ref>\n| Feature film\n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Lazer Team 2]]''\n| Zach<ref name=\":0\" />\n| Feature film\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2014\u20132019\n| ''[[Fairy Tail#Anime|Fairy Tail]]''\n| [[List of Fairy Tail characters#Sting Eucliffe|Sting Eucliffe]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.funimation.com/blog/2014/08/09/awesome-english-cast-announcements-from-otakon/ |date=August 9, 2014 |title=Awesome English Cast Announcements from Otakon |publisher=[[Funimation]] |author=Michelle |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811202845/http://www.funimation.com/blog/2014/08/09/awesome-english-cast-announcements-from-otakon/ |archive-date=August 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-08-09/4-more-cast-members-join-funimation-fairy-tail-dub/.77376 |work=[[Anime News Network]] |date=August 9, 2014 |title=4 More Cast Members Join Funimation's Fairy Tail Dub |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811212755/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-08-09/4-more-cast-members-join-funimation-fairy-tail-dub/.77376 |archive-date=August 11, 2014}}</ref>\n| Television series; English version\n|-\n| rowspan= \"3\" | 2015\n| ''[[World Break: Aria of Curse for a Holy Swordsman]]''\n|  Gen<ref>{{cite news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731014809/http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/177683/20150223/world-break-curse-of-aria-for-a-holy-swordsman-english-dub-funimation-clifford-chapin-felecia-angelle-jad-saxton.htm |archive-date=31 July 2016 |url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/177683/20150223/world-break-curse-of-aria-for-a-holy-swordsman-english-dub-funimation-clifford-chapin-felecia-angelle-jad-saxton.htm |date=February 23, 2015 |first=Tara |last=Edwards |publisher=KpopStarz |title='World Break: Aria Of Curse For A Holy Swordsman' English Dub Cast Revealed By Funimation, Includes Clifford Chapin, Felecia Angelle, Jad Saxton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422045546/http://www.funimation.com/blog/2015/02/19/world-break-aria-of-curse-for-a-holy-swordsman-cast-announcement/#more-9867 |archive-date=April 22, 2016 |url=http://www.funimation.com/blog/2015/02/19/world-break-aria-of-curse-for-a-holy-swordsman-cast-announcement/ |date=February 19, 2015 |title=World Break \u2013 Aria of Curse for a Holy Swordsman Cast Announcement |publisher=[[Funimation]] |author=Michelle}}</ref>\n| Television series; English version\n|-\n| ''[[Dragonar Academy]]''\n| Additional Cast\n| Television series; English version\n|-\n| ''[[Ninja Slayer#Anime|Ninja Slayer From Animation]]''\n| Rapture\n| Television series; English version\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[